<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Germans Still Reluctant to Embrace Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 22 (Xinhua) -- With the planned advent of the
single European currency, the euro, just eight months away, a
majority of Germans are still dismayed about abandoning their
cherished German marks in favor of the untested new currency, a
German opinion poll showed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The poll commissioned by the German ZDF television network
found that 62.4 percent of Germans opposed the euro and only 32.7
percent supported it.
</P>
<P>
The main concern shared by many Germans was still the possible
inflation risks due to the introduction of the euro, the survey
showed. Among 1,347 people questioned, 43.3 percent said they
believed that the cost of living would rise after the currency
switch.
</P>
<P>
Following a European Union road map, the euro will be launched
in January 1999. But at first it will only be used in financial
exchanges in the expected 11 euro zone countries. The actual notes
and coins will be introduced over a six-month period starting
January 1, 2002, after which the participants' present national
currencies will cease to be legal tender.
</P>
<P>
Both houses of the German parliament are due to vote later this
week on Germany's adoption of the euro. With broad support from
both the ruling and major opposition parties, an approval is
believed to be certain.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
