<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada to Lead G-7 Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Canada is posed to lead the G-7
countries in economic growth through this year and next, according
to the latest economic forecast by the Royal Bank of Canada.
</P>
<P>
Canadian growth is expected to reach 3.2 percent this year and
2.8 percent next year, the bank's economists predicted.
</P>
<P>
"We believe the Canadian economy's underlying momentum will
carry us through to two years of good growth," John MacCallum,
chief economist of the bank was quoted as saying by reports
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Canada's economic growth has been mostly
export-driven. But in 1998-99, it will be a "made-in-Canada"
story, the forecast said.
</P>
<P>
Domestic growth will be fueled by largely low interest rates,
strong domestic demand and a pro-investment attitude from Canadian
businesses, it noted.
</P>
<P>
Of the provinces, Alberta will post the strongest growth over
the next two years, followed by Ontario, Newfoundland and Nova
Scotia. British Columbia will have the weakest.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the bank said there are risks to its rosy expectations,
including a deepening of the Asian crisis, weaker prices of
commodities, high consumer debt and a U.S. stock market
correction.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
