<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientist With Strategic View Becomes New Model </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government has chosen
a scientist who was known for being able to examine things from a
strategic point of view and to tailor his research to the needs of
the nation as a new model for Chinese scientists.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Xinsong, who died of a heart attack in 1997 at the age of
66 and who is known as the "father of Chinese robotics", was
chosen as an example of one who could apply the policy of
rejuvenating the nation with science and technology, which is a
major priority of China's new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, who was a member of the Chinese Academy of Engineering
and a leading member of a national automation project, contributed
enormously to a deep-sea robot that can work at a depth of 6,000
meters.
</P>
<P>
Li Xueyong, Vice-minister of Science and Technology, told a
meeting held to commemorate Jiang in Beijing today, that he was
not only good at scientific research and development, but also
capable of making decisions in accordance with the overall
situation. And it was Jiang, he said, who helped the rapid
development of the robotics industry in the early 1980s, and
suggested that China develop its own robots for deep-sea
exploration.
</P>
<P>
He was also deeply interested in the development of large and
middle-sized enterprises in China and developed the Computer
Integrated Manufacturing System, which has been used in factories
in different provinces and municipalities to improve their profit.
</P>
<P>
A Chinese Academy of Sciences official says that Jiang believed
that scientific research should focus on major projects connected
to the needs of the nation and that the Academy should maintain a
strong team for those projects.
</P>
<P>
Jiang contributed many suggestions on the development of
science and technology in China that still fit China's scientific
reform and development principles even now, the official said,
adding that the country needs scientists like him with strategic
views. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
