<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Calls for Jobs for Demobilized Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin said here
today that local governments should provide jobs for demobilized
soldiers and help them receive proper job training.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the remarks at the National Resettlement Conference
for Demobilized Soldiers.
</P>
<P>
This year, some 50,000 officers of the People's Liberation Army
and the armed police will be transferred to civilian work and the
number will grow in 1999 and 2000. This is in accordance with the
country's announcement last October to cut its armed forces by
500,000 by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that reducing the size of the armed forces is an
important step in modernizing the Chinese army and that
resettlement for the demobilized soldiers has a direct bearing on
the success of the strategy.
</P>
<P>
Although the resettlement this year faces tremendous
difficulties, because it coincides with the government's
institutional restructuring and state enterprise reforms, local
governments should overcome all difficulties to see to it that
those demobilized officers are properly trained and employed,
Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said the military should help the demobilized soldiers
understand the current situation and combine personal interest
with the need of the Party and the country and cooperate with
local governments.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the resettlement work needs to be reformed
to suit the socialist market economy and asked military and
civilian departments to begin doing research on that. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
