<HEADLINE> Kuwait Supports Lebanon's Position on Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Speaker of the National
Assembly Ahmed Abdul Aziz Al-Sadoun said here Wednesday that his
country fully supported Lebanese government's position concerning
the Israeli withdrawal offer from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sadoun made the remarks upon his arrival here for a
three-day official visit at the invitation of his Lebanese
counterpart Nabih Berri, according to Lebanese official National
News Agency.
</P>
<P>
He called on Israel to withdraw its troops from south Lebanon
immediately and unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli cabinet formally approved on April 1 the U.N.
Resolution 425 and offered to withdraw its troops from south
Lebanon provided negotiated security arrangements are agreed by
the Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and its ally Syria firmly rejected the offer on the
grounds that it contradicted the U.N. resolution which calls for
an unconditional Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon, saying that the
pullout must be unconditional.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer border strip in south
Lebanon in 1985 with the aim of protecting its northern
settlements from Lebanese guerrilla cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sadoun, who came here from Syria, is expected to meet
Lebanese President Elias Hrawi and Prime Minister Rafik Hariri
for discussions on bilateral ties and regional affairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
