<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UUP Leader Denounces Killing in Northern Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- David Trimble, leader of the
pro-British Ulster Unionist Party (UUP), on Wednesday denounced
the murder of a Roman Catholic that has cast a shadow over hopes
for peace in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with BBC Radio, Trimble described the suspected
Protestant murderers as "corrupt and degenerate" and predicted the
path to stability would not be easy.
</P>
<P>
Adrian Lamph, 29, was shot dead on Tuesday by a lone gunman in
a yard at a municipal depot in the mainly Protestant town of
Portadown.
</P>
<P>
It was the first apparently sectarian killing since pro-Irish
Roman Catholic and pro-British Protestant parties reached an
agreement on April 10 to end the 30-year-old conflict in the
province.
</P>
<P>
No group has claimed responsibility of the murder, but media
reports accused the outlawed Loyalist Volunteer Front (LVF), a
dissident militant group which killed several Catholic
nationalists in a campaign aimed at derailing the 22-month
multiparty peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Trimble said he was "appalled and disgusted at what has
happened." "I have to say to the handful of corrupt and degenerate
people who are responsible for this...nothing will be achieved, no
cause will be served by this sort of action."
</P>
<P>
But he was adamant that peace efforts would bear fruit, despite
setbacks along the way.
</P>
<P>
"The hope will be fulfilled -- but it's not going to be easy,
it's not going to be a smooth road," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
