<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ireland Overtakes UK In World League Table </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Republic of Ireland has
overtaken the United Kingdom in the world league table of economic
performance, according to a study released here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The annual study of 46 countries from a Swiss-based think-tank
showed Britain slipping one place to 12th out of the 15 economies
in the first rank.
</P>
<P>
The decline in the UK's performance, which follows a climb from
19th last year, was attributed to the strength of the pound, which
harmed the country's competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
The study said that Ireland continued to be the "Tiger of
Europe" with the government's policy of attracting inward
investment responsible for "staggering growth" over the past few
years. Its rating has gone up from 22nd two years ago to 11th.
</P>
<P>
While Ireland has been the success story of the past few years,
other countries in Europe - including the three big economies of
Germany, France and Italy - have fared less well.
</P>
<P>
The International Institute for Management Development (IMD)
said Germany had dropped from sixth position in the mid-1990s to
14th - second to bottom of the first division.
</P>
<P>
France slipped two places to 21st, while Italy, despite some
improvement over the past 12 months, was rooted at the bottom of
the second division in 32th position.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. topped the league, with the IMD saying that only
complacency or a major stockmarket crash could threaten a
situation that is "historically exceptional".
</P>
<P>
Japan has suffered a nine-place drop to 18th that "reflects a
complete disarray of the economy", the institute said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
