<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Launches New Crackdown on "Booze" Smugglers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Britain on Wednesday announced new
measures to crack down alcohol, beer and cigarettes smugglers who
swindle customs out of nearly one billion pounds (1.7 billion U.S.
dollars) a year.
</P>
<P>
Customs minister Dawn Primarolo said that under new proposals,
persistent offenders face the loss of their vehicles and may be
disqualified from driving.
</P>
<P>
"The government is committed to cracking down on tobacco and
alcohol smuggling and this tough package will send a message that
smuggling does not pay," she said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Under European rules, Britons are allowed to return home with
hefty allowances of spirits, wine, beer and tobacco for their own
personal use. And big tax differentials between Britain and the
continent have spawned bootlegging on a giant scale.
</P>
<P>
The huge profits on offer have attracted criminal gangs whose
activities have pushed up beer imports by 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Primarolo said offenders may also have to pay compensation for
revenue evaded through smuggling, while owners of shops and
restaurants selling smuggled alcohol could lose their liquor
licenses.
</P>
<P>
British Customs offices made more than 8,700 seizures of
alcohol and tobacco last year and confiscated 2,929 vehicles used
by smugglers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania Promulgates Bankruptcy Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Romania's President Emil
Constantinescu Wednesday promulgated the law on winding up
troubled banks, announced the information office of the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
The bankruptcy law was drafted with the help of Romania's
Central Bank, the International Monetary Fund and the United
States Agency for International Development in line with
international standards.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, a bank whose liabilities exceed assets can ask a
court to rule the winding up under the new legislation. The
Central Bank will appeal to the court against a bank which fails
to make payments after special monitoring and administration
measures have been futily applied. The court will notify the
Central Bank on its decision as to beginning winding up the
troubled bank.
</P>
<P>
The law sets precise deadlines for procedures needed to declare
insolvent a bank that has posted safe, liquid and exigible amounts
in credit if this bank ceases payments for at least 30 days.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank will close the insolvent bank's accounts
immediately, and open an account called "bank under insolvency".
This account will become recipient of all the amounts of money in
the bank's accounts to that date. Any forthcoming financial
operation of the bank will unfold exclusively through this unique
account.
</P>
<P>
Winding up will be closed after the court has approved the
final report, all the funds or assets of the insolvent bank have
been distributed, and the unclaimed funds have been deposited with
the Central Bank.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
