<HEADLINE> Reppas: Greece Decides to Join EMU in Second Stage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas said Wednesday that Greece had decided to join the
European Union's Economic and Monetary Union (EMU) in 2001 due to
the economic situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing, Reppas said that it was very
difficult for Greece to enter the EMU in 1999 because such a move
might harm the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
Although the recent rise in the Athens Stock Exchange index,
which soared Tuesday 7.32 percent to end at 2,627.90 points,
showed a positive development of the Greek economy, much an
effort was still necessary for Greece to meet the EU targets set
out by the Maastricht treaty, he added.
</P>
<P>
To quicken its pace for the entry into the EMU, Greece allowed
its national currency in March to join the European exchange rate
mechanism (ERM) and announced a series of drastic structural
measures including the part-privatilization of 11 state-run
enterprises and banks in the next 18 months.  
</P>
