<HEADLINE> Annan Recommends to Extend Mandate of MONUA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 22 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Wednesday recommended to extend the mandate of the
United Nations observer Mission in Angola (MONUA) for a further
period of two months until June 20, 1998.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the Security Council of the United Nations,
Annan said significant progress has been achieved in Angolan peace
process, although the remaining tasks under the Lusaka Protocol
were not fully completed by the March 31, 1998 deadline agreed
upon by the Angolan Government and the National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General said he welcomed important developments
which include the promulgation into law of the special status of
Savimbi, the leader of UNITA, the appointment of the governors and
vice-governors nominated by UNITA, the return of some UNITA senior
officials to Luanda and the termination of Radio Vorgan's
broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief said he is concerned at the low pace of the
implementation of the extension of State administration, which
should also have been completed by March 31.
</P>
<P>
He said the security situation is deteriorating in the country
with increased attacks against the Angolan National Police, local
government authorities and innocent civilians, and UNITA continue
to impose restrictions on United Nations activities in some of the
region still under its control.
</P>
<P>
Annan once again reminded both parties that they are
responsible for ensuring the safety and security of all United
Nations personnel in Angola.  
</P>
</TEXT>
