<HEADLINE> Siemens Lowers Profit Forecasts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Germany's electronics giant Siemens said
Wednesday that its full-year net profit for the current fiscal year
ending September 30 may not reach three billion German marks (1.7
billion U.S. dollars) as expected earlier.
</P>
<P>
A Siemens spokeswoman attributed the lowered profit expectations
mainly to the company's increased risk provisions in Asia due to the
recent financial crisis as well as a drop in computer chip prices on
the world market.
</P>
<P>
However, the company still expected its full-year turnover to rise
to between 110 billion to 115 billion marks (between 62 billion to 65
billion dollars) from last year's 107 billion marks (60 billion
dollars), the spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of the 1997-1998 business year, the company's
turnover climbed by 17 percent to 52.1 billion marks (29 billion
dollars). The first-half net profit was also up 10 percent to 1.19
billion marks (670 million dollars).  
</P>
