<HEADLINE> Zambia to Introduce New Registration Cards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Zambia will introduce new
computerized and forge proof national registration cards to
replace the old ones, home affairs minister Peter Machungwa said
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The new cards to be produced by an Israeli computer company
have special security features and contains more details than the
old ones making them difficult to forge and tamper with, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the issuance of the new cards will start soon before
the local government elections expected to be held in June.
</P>
<P>
The two-phased exercise expected to complete in the year 2000
will cost the country 11.2 million U.S. dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the first phase the new cards will be issued only to
applicants who have lost their cards and those who have reached
the age of 16 and in the second phase all the old ones will be
replaced, he said.
</P>
<P>
The new cards are durable and will help safeguard national
security unlike in the past when aliens manipulated the old cards
and presented themselves as Zambians through fraudulently
obtained cards, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Machungwa said the government will find it easier to manage
and utilize the national registration information for the benefit
of the nation because it will be processed and stored on the
computer and not done manually as in the past. 
</P>
</TEXT>
