<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Zambia paid 160.032 million U.S.
Dollars last year servicing its foreign debt, which now stands at
about 7.1 billion Dollars, State House spokesman Richard Sakala
said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman told a news briefing that in the first quarter
of this year his country paid 38.763 million Dollars to both
multilateral and Paris Club creditors.
</P>
<P>
From April to the end of this year 161.59 million more Dollars
will be paid to service the country's foreign debt, he said.
</P>
<P>
Payments to multilateral creditors, like the World Bank,
International Monetary Fund (IMF) and African Development Bank
(ADB) are projected to be 79.74 million Dollars, representing
49.3 percent of the total amount.
</P>
<P>
A sum of 54 million Dollars will be paid to the Paris Club
creditors representing 33.4 percent while payments to non Paris
Club creditors are projected to be 25 million Dollars
representing 15.5 percent. The remaining balance is projected as
payments to financial institutions, he said. 
