<HEADLINE> Son of President Mitterrand Defends Father's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The son of President Francois
Mitterrand, Jean-Christophe Mitterrand, Wednesday defended his
father's policy toward Rwanda prior to the 1994 genocide.
</P>
<P>
Mitterrand was accused of supporting the Hutu military regime
headed by President Juvenal Habyarimana until the latter was
killed in a missile attack on his plane on April 6, 1994.
</P>
<P>
"If one wants to objectively sum up the action of France in
Rwanda in this period, he is obliged to say that the president of
the republic (Mitterrand) spared no efforts to make the regime of
President Habyaramina evolve toward multiparty system and
democracy," said Jean-Christophe Mitterrand.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Christophe, who served as special advisor for African
affairs for his father from 1986 to 1992, was summoned by the
commission of information of the National Assembly investigating
if there was any role played by France in the 1994 genocide in
Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
He also denied that he used to make secret missions to Africa
for his father.
</P>
<P>
"I made in 10 years only one secret trip, which had nothing to
do with Rwanda, at the request of President Mitterrand and in
agreement with the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Secretariat
of State for Cooperation," he said.
</P>
<P>
During a previous hearing held on Tuesday, four former
government ministers of France in the last years of the Mitterrand
era, including former Prime Minister Edouard Balladur, also denied
any French involvement in the genocide perpetrated by the Hutu
military regime against the Tutsis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
