<HEADLINE> Women Organization not to Support Paula Jones Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Citing overwhelming opposition
of its national board and local chapters, the National
Organization for Women (NOW) said Wednesday it will not file legal
papers on behalf of Paula Jones in her sexual harassment lawsuit
against President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
NOW President Patricia Ireland told a news conference the
women's group believes such a "highly charged political" lawsuit
should not be used as a test case for stopping sexual harassment
in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
Ms. Ireland also said her group "decided not to work with the
disreputable right-wing organizations and individuals advancing
her cause, who themselves have a long-standing political interest
in undermining our movement to strengthen women's rights and
weakening the laws that protect those rights."
</P>
<P>
Ireland said, it was clear from contacts with about 500
chapters around the country that the local groups opposed filing a
friend-of-the-court brief, by margins of at least 8-to-1 and
possibly 10-to-1.
</P>
<P>
"Hard cases make bad law," Ms. Ireland said. The conservative
Rutherford Institute, which is financing legal expenses for Mrs.
Jones, and her spokeswoman Susan Carpenter McMillan is "using
this case to advance their own political agendas," she said.
</P>
<P>
Ms. Ireland said, "Paula Jones has surrounded herself with a
phalanx of politically motivated lawyers."  
</P>
</TEXT>
