<HEADLINE> UK Parliament Votes Overwhelmingly for N. Irish Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The British parliament voted 350
to 11 on Wednesday to cut short usual procedures and rush through
the bill providing for elections to a new assembly on June 25.
</P>
<P>
The bill will be followed by a second, fuller piece of
constitutional legislation which will implement other parts of the
peaceful settlement, Northern Ireland minister Paul Murphy told
parliament after the voting.
</P>
<P>
Opposition Conservatives have expressed their support for the
peace accord and for the bill, which implements one of the key
provisions of the multi-party peace agreement brokered on April
10.
</P>
<P>
The elections to the 108-seat assembly will go ahead if the
peace deal is approved by a referendum on May 22.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland has been under direct rule from London since
its previous assembly was shut down in 1973 as the province
erupted in violence.
</P>
<P>
In the new assembly, unlike the old Protestant-dominated
legislature, power will be shared out in an executive picked on a
proportional basis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
