<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania-Japan Trade Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's trade with
Japan saw a downward trend in 1997 with exports decreasing by
12.7 percent from the previous year, a report issued by the Japan
External Trade Organization in Dar es Salaam said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's exports to Japan dropped to 59
million U.S. Dollars in 1997 from 67.5 million U.S. Dollars in
1996 last year, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Imports from Japan, however, rose to 79.5 million U.S. Dollars
from 77.4 million U.S. Dollars, a rise of 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's trade deficit recorded more than 20 million U.S.
Dollars which suggests that the east African country needs to
increase its exports to Japan in order to harmonize the trade
balance between the two countries, the report pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed last year's downward trend in the trade
to the deteriorating economic situation in Japan which led to a
decrease in the purchasing power.
</P>
<P>
Among the goods exported to Japan, coffee ranked first in
terms of export volume, which stood at 32.8 million U.S. Dollars.
Coming up next were fish fillets and sesame seeds, with 10.2
million US dollars and 10.1 million U.S. Dollars in trade volume
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Exports of the crops, however, had decreased by 2.8 percent,
17 percent and 21.5 percent respectively from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Tanzania exported cloves worth nearly 329,000 U.S.
Dollars, equivalent to 62.7 percent of the total world supply of
the crop to Japan. The country was followed by Malaysia, and
Madagascar had an share of 24.4 percent and 5.4 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Tanzania's exports to Japan were
mainly consisted of raw materials while imports were dominated by
manufactured goods.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
