<HEADLINE> Nigeria Adopts New Policy on Solid Minerals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The government of Nigeria,
Africa's leading oil producer, has approved new national policy
on solid minerals in an effort to fully tap the rich natural
resources of the country.
</P>
<P>
Under the policy, areas relevant to viable economic
development of the sector will be clearly addressed, according to
Solid Minerals Development Minister Alhaji Kaloma Ali.
</P>
<P>
The policy was approved together with a review and revision of
the outdated mining laws of 1946 and allied regulations last
weekend when the ministry celebrated its third anniversary, the
News Agency of Nigeria reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The policy, said the minister, also pays attention to the role
of the state and organized private sector, deregulation of
minerals exploitation, manpower development, incentives to
investors in mining and the need for an orderly development.
</P>
<P>
All impediments to process for entry into the country's mining
industry have been removed with the adoption of the revised
mining laws and regulations.
</P>
<P>
The new laws were fashioned out such as to facilitate decision
making in investment placement and to ensure smooth operations in
the mining fields and minerals trade, Ali said.
</P>
<P>
He also announced the break-up of the monopoly enjoyed
previously by the Nigerian Coal Corporation in the prospecting,
mining, processing and marketing of coal in the country.
</P>
<P>
The former corporation has earlier established joint ventures
for the exploitation of gold, magnesium, kaolin and barytes.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that the approval of the new policy and
laws shows the government's determination to reduce the country's
overdependence on oil so as to boost economic restructuring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
