<HEADLINE> EIA Urges UK for Action to Protect Whales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 22 (Xinhua) - Many species and populations of
small whales, dolphins and porpoises face continued decline and
extinction due to mass killings in unregulated hunts all over the
world, the Environmental Investigation Agency (EIA) warned here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The EIA is urging the UK Government on the eve of the convening
of its new "Whaling Forum" to press for immediate action to
conserve and protect the 68 species of small whales which are not
covered by the IWC (the International Whaling Commission) ban on
commercial whale hunle
conservation and will advise the Government on the development of
its policies on whaling and whale conservation.
</P>
<P>
Steve Trent, EIA's Campaign Director said Wednesday: "Tens of
thousands of dolphins, porpoises and small whales are killed in
unregulated hunts all over the world."
</P>
<P>
"The new Labor Government has a unique opportunity to guarantee
the survival of these threatened species for the next Millennium
by pressing for urgent IWC action," he added.
</P>
<P>
The EIA is a non profit environmental group which works to
conserve and protect wildlife, their habitats and the natural
environment.
</P>
<P>
The Agency has been campaigning for the past 13 years for
greater international protection for the 68 species of small
cetaceans which are not included in the IWC's ban on commercial
hunting of whales. 
</P>
