<HEADLINE> Round-up: Arab Anti-Terrorism Pact Signed to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Arab interior and justice ministers
from the 22-member Arab League (AL) signed a trail-blazing pact
here Wednesday on enhancing cooperation for fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed at the joint meetings of the Arab
interior and justice ministers councils which opened Wednesday
morning to finalize the joint anti-terrorism strategy.
</P>
<P>
Arab League Secretary General Esmat Abdel-Meguid and
delegations from the AL's 22 member states witnessed the signing
of the first Arab anti-terrorism deal in the Cairo-based AL
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The pact, whose negotiations started in 1987, calls for
boosting cooperation among the signatory states to develop a
system for preventing and combating terrorist crimes.
</P>
<P>
It says that signatory states should brief each other
immediately on any terrorist crime that might take place in its
territories, including exchanging data relevant to terrorist
crimes, activists, training places and sources of funds.
</P>
<P>
Among other significant articles in the anti-terrorism pact was
that the signatories pledge to extradite those allegedly involved
in terrorist crimes through diplomatic or justice means.
</P>
<P>
The agreement opposes any possible attempts of the signatory
states to organize, finance, commit or take part in terrorist acts
in any way.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the pact confirms the right of the people to armed
struggle against foreign occupation and aggression.
</P>
<P>
It legitimizes the struggle to liberate occupied lands, obtain
the right to self-determination and independence and maintain
national unity according to the principles and resolutions of the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Interior Minister Prince Nayef Bin Abdel-Aziz, also
chairman of the conference, termed the pact as a major achievement
on the road to joint Arab action, saying it would help realize
security and stability for the Arab nations.
</P>
<P>
In his inaugural speech, Abdel-Meguid hailed the signing of the
agreement as a "leading significant step along the joint Arab
security march."
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Interior Minister Habib Ibrahim el-Adli said the
signing of the agreement signaled that the Arab nations have
finally reached an agreement on the issue and hammered out a
complete set of anti-terrorism strategy.
</P>
<P>
In Egypt, almost 1,300 people have died in terrorism-related
accidents since Muslim militants began a violent campaign against
the secular government in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The country lost 2.2 billion U.S. dollars in tourism revenues
in 1997 alone due to a series of terrorist attacks against
foreigners last year.
</P>
<P>
Algerian Interior Minister Mostefa Benmansour confirmed that
"daily and careful implementation of the articles of the agreement
by all Arab states will definitely uproot this phenomenon that
contradicts Arab values and the tolerance of Islam."
</P>
<P>
Muslim insurgency has killed an estimated 75,000 people in
Algeria since the government canceled the 1992 legislative
elections that the now-banned Islamic Salvation Front was on the
verge of winning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
