<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Pupils to Donate School Bags for Iraqi Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates
Wednesday launched a campaign for pupils to donate 25,000 school
bags for Iraqi children whose country suffers badly from the
seven-year-old U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the start of the campaign, the Red Crescent Society
of the United Arab Emirate (UAE) called on each UAE pupil to
donate 20 dirhams (5.45 U.S. dollars), the cost of one school bag
together with some school tools and copybooks.
</P>
<P>
The school bags are to be sent to Iraq by the end of the
current school year and to be distributed at the beginning of the
coming school year.
</P>
<P>
Some Iraqi artists will hold an exhibition here from May 12 to
18. Some 120 portraits will be exhibited and put for sale. Half of
the proceeds will go to the campaign fund.
</P>
<P>
This campaign is actually complementary to that of collecting
foodstuffs and medicine launched by the UAE Red Crescent Society
over two years ago to help Iraqi children and women.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions were imposed on Iraq after its 1990 invasion
of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
