<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Gains Support on Kiriyenko Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
announced on Thursday that both leaders of the parliament, Yegor
Stroyev and Gennady Seleznyov, had given tentative support to his
nominee for prime minister, Sergei Kiriyenko.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin described an one-hour meeting with the leaders on
Thursday morning as, "the last or most decisive roundtable, but
not the last or most decisive battle", the Itar-Tass news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, which was reportedly held in a warm and
constructive atmosphere, Federal Council Speaker Stroyev told a
news briefing that the upper house had adopted an address to the
State Duma to find a calm solution.
</P>
<P>
He said: "At the moment, the stake is not on Kiriyenko, but on
the future of Russia and of the Federal Assembly. Every deputy is
contemplating this."
</P>
<P>
According to the presidential press service, Yeltsin will
address a letter to the State Duma, or the lower house of the
parliament, to ask for an approval of Kiriyenko's nomination. But
the president had no plan to visit the Duma Friday, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, on Thursday, also had a 20-minute telephone
conversation with Gennady Zyuganov, leader of the Communist Party
faction in the Duma.
</P>
<P>
He told Zyuganov to "think not of your party and personality,
but about the state, about stability in the country."
</P>
<P>
Duma Chairman Gennady Seleznyov told the press after a plenary
session of the Communist Party Central Committee Thursday that
most communists in Friday's vote favored "preserving the Duma"
while confirming Kiriyenko as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin also held discussions with Kiriyenko Thursday, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The Duma will vote for the last time on the president's nominee
for the premiership Friday.
</P>
<P>
It had rejected the nomination twice. If it fails to approve
Kiriyenko as prime minister on the third vote, it would be
dissolved by the president under the Russian Constitution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
