<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Refuses to Patent Harvard Mouse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Canada has turned down Harvard
University's attempt to patent a type of high-tech mouse that gets
cancer easily.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Court of Canada ruled here Wednesday that the
cancer-prone mouse is not "an invention" under Canadian law.
</P>
<P>
The mouse was genetically engineered by Harvard to help in
cancer research. It has already patented in the United Stated.
</P>
<P>
The patent gives Harvard the sole right to create any mice with
these genes, breed them, own them and decide who may use them.
</P>
<P>
When Harvard asked Canadian patent bureau to follow suit, it
was refused by Canadian officials. So Harvard appealed to the
Federal Court.
</P>
<P>
In delivering his ruling, Federal Judge Marc Nadon notes that
Harvard invented a method of injecting mouse cells with a
cancer-prone gene, "but they have not invented the mouse."
</P>
<P>
"A complex life form does not fit within the current parameters
of the Patent Act without stretching the meaning of the words to
the breaking point, which I am not prepared to do," he writes.
</P>
<P>
Harvard's David Morrow said he had sent a copy of the judgement
to the university, which hasn't had time to react.
</P>
<P>
Environment groups here welcomed the ruling, saying that it
helps to prevent the concentration of too much control over
animals and medical research in the hands of a small number of
corporations.
</P>
<P>
But biotech companies counters that patents such as this will
protect their investment in expensive research from their rivals.
</P>
<P>
So far, Canada has granted patents to only single-life forms such
as a yeast culture, but not to mammals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prices of Iranian Staple Food Sharply Raised </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The prices of Iran's traditional
staple bread "Nan" have risen by 20-50 percent as the government
moved to check the colossal and widespread waste of food.
</P>
<P>
The Salam daily reported Thursday that the price rise would
help remedy people's ignorance of the heavy government subsidies
that have kept Nan affordable to low-income and poor families.
</P>
<P>
After the price hike, a piece of Nan weighing 170 grams is sold
for 60 rials (about one U.S. cent).
</P>
<P>
The authorities have complained that Iranians waste 500 million
U.S. dollars of Nan every year.
</P>
<P>
According to Salam, even after the price hikes the government
still has to pay more each year for Nan to beat the country's
two-digit inflation.
</P>
<P>
Salam said government subsidies to Nan were expected to reach
5,120 billion rials (about 1.7 billion dollars) during the current
Iranian calendar year (starting March 21), up 17 percent from that
of last year.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the government's price support, Nan has become all
along cheaper in terms of an ordinary Iranian's purchase power.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. dollar can buy nearly 100 pieces of Nan in comparison to
the then rate of one against 15 two decades ago, while an ordinary
Iranian salary earner's payment still remains within the range
between 80 to 100 U.S. dollars during the period.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Majlis (parliament) on Tuesday held a closed-door
session with the participation of two cabinet ministers to discuss
Nan wastage in the country.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also shed light on serious economic hardship in
Iran, which is expected to face a 4 billion-dollar shortfall in
revenues due to a slump in oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The Tehran Radio reported Wednesday that Iran may be forced to
redrafted its budget due to the oil price crisis caused by
oversupply on the international crude markets and slackened demand
around the globe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
