<HEADLINE> Report: French Damage Plan to Arrest Karadzic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- France damaged a plan by the
U.S.-led allied forces in Bosnia to arrest the former Bosnian Serb
leader Radovan Karadzic late last summer, U.S. newspapers reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and allied forces had to shelve the plans after
Washington discovered that a senior French military officer had
held secret meetings with Karadzic, The Washington Post quoted
senior U.S. and diplomatic officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The series of clandestine meetings convinced U.S. officials
that key details of the arrest plans might have been leaked
directly to the fugitive Serb leader by the officer, a French Army
major named Herve Gourmillon," said the post.
</P>
<P>
A similar report was also made by The New York Times. The
secret meetings between Gourmillon and Karadzic deeply troubled
the Americans and other NATO allies and undercut trust in the
French military, it reported.
</P>
<P>
The post said that the French has acknowledged the meetings but
have said that the officers acted on his own. Gourmillon was
reassigned to Paris and suffered no punishment for his actions.
</P>
<P>
The times quoted officials as saying that the west is still
planning to arrest Karadzic despite the wariness about the French
military.
</P>
<P>
They pointed to recent exercises where NATO-led troops occupied
police headquarters and other buildings in Pale, measures which
have helped drive Karadzic underground, the paper added.
</P>
<P>
"But officials also cautioned that a raid to capture Dr.
Karadzic is not imminent," it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
