<HEADLINE> Tung Chee Hwa Reaffirms SAR Govt Support to Sports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) reaffirmed
here on Thursday his government's full support to the SAR's
long-term sports development by repeating his promise of financial
backing.
</P>
<P>
He recalled the promise he made early last year when he was
running for the election of SAR's Chief Executive. Tung promised
strong financial support from the SAR government when he spoke at
a function held by the Hong Kong Sports Development Board.
</P>
<P>
But the SAR Chief did not mean to give money deliberately. "I
hope the money are wisely used," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tung was speaking at a cocktail party Thursday evening given by
the Amateur Sports Federation and Olympic Committee (ASF&AMP;OC) of
Hong Kong, China in honor of the former President A.O. de Sales,
who had served as ASF&AMP;OC chief for the past 44 years.
</P>
<P>
"We believe sports can only thrive in dignity and independence
with material backing from the government," said Timothy Fok,
President of the ASF&AMP;OC.
</P>
<P>
"With a larger public subsidy, out athletes and coaches can
concentrate on their pursuits, free from financial worries. With
a strong sports culture, our people will be strengthened in body,
spirit, virtue and unity," he added.
</P>
<P>
The newly-elected local sports chief also praised local sports
association leaders for their "sacrifice out of passion for
sports."
</P>
<P>
Among those present at the cocktail party were SAR Government
officials, local sports association leaders, and a delegation from
 the International Olympic Committee (IOC), led by Kim Un Yong,
South Korea's IOC vice-president. Kim was an envoy for IOC
President Juan Antonio Samaranch. Among the delegates were IOC
Executive Board member He Zhenliang from China and IOC member Wu
Ching-Kuo from Chinese Taipei.
</P>
<P>
Also present at the party was Ma Yuzhen, Commissioner of the
Chinese Foreign Ministry in the Hong Kong SAR. 
</P>
