<HEADLINE> France Recognizes Link Between Officer with Karadzic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- France Thursday recognized that
there could have existed an abnormal relationship between a French
military officer serving in the NATO force in Bosnia and the
Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic, wanted for war crime
charges.
</P>
<P>
The French Defense Ministry said that the relations between
Commander Herve Gourmelon and Karadzic "could have appeared
contestable".
</P>
<P>
The defense ministry made the statement in response to an
accusation by the United States officials that Gourmelon tipped
off to Karadzic the plan by NATO force to arrest him a couple of
times in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The American daily Washington Post Thursday quoted U.S.
officials as saying that Gourmelon met Karadzic several times and
that a U.S. plan to arrest the Serb leader was cancelled because
of fear that Karadzic was tipped off beforehand.
</P>
<P>
The accusation by the United States could confirm an earlier
accusation by the General Prosecutor of the International Tribunal
for judging war crimes in former Yugoslavia, Louise Arbour, that
France refused to cooperate with the tribunal to arrest Serb war
crime suspects.
</P>
<P>
However, France said that it had fully cooperated with the
tribunal in arresting a number of other Serb criminals hiding the
zone controlled by French troops in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
"In this case, a French official kept different contacts, as
the orders he received made it possible," said the French Defense
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
"As soon as the conditions for carrying out these relations
could have appeared contestable, this official was immediately
received a new assignment in France," it added.
</P>
<P>
Gourmelon, who used to serve as NATO spokesman in Sarajevo, was
recalled to France for "family reasons" in 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
