<HEADLINE> Mkapa Invites Zimbabwean Investors to Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa Thursday urged Zimbabwean business circles to
invest in his country which offers a lot of opportunities for
foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa, who arrived on Wednesday in Harare for a four-day state
visit to Zimbabwe, said Tanzania's economy had over the years
been transformed from a public-enterprise-driven economy to one
driven by the private sector with the government playing a
facilitating role.
</P>
<P>
He told Zimbabwean businessmen and company executives at a
breakfast meeting in Harare that his government had so far
offloaded 174 parastatals out of a total of 300 in its bid to
make the private sector the engine of economic growth, the
Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said local businessmen could take advantage of his
government's privatisation program to invest in the country
through acquiring stakes in the remaining 126 state-owned
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"The privatisation process is done by public tender where we
advertise for bids and the highest bidder is assured of winning
the tender," he said.
</P>
<P>
"A number of South African companies have acquired some of the
parastatals prompting people in Tanzania to complain that we are
becoming an extension of South Africa, so I urge you to also come
and invest in these companies," Mkapa said.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether Tanzanians were being given the opportunity to
buy the public enterprises, Mkapa said, at the moment most of
them did not have the capital.
</P>
<P>
But the government was retaining certain percentages of stakes
in strategic companies and warehousing the shares for them to buy
later.
</P>
<P>
Trade and investment opportunities between Tanzania and
Zimbabwe exist in food processing, agriculture, construction,
horticulture, mining, textile and clothing, pharmaceutical and
service sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
