<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Expects Better Telecommunication Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Kenya needs some 5.4 billion
U.S. Dollars to improve telecommunication services nationwide in
an effort to industrialize itself by 2020, experts said at the
first-ever Telecom East Africa Exhibition opening Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Kenya plans to raise penetration from the present 0.16 lines
per 100 people to one line per 100 people in rural areas and from
four lines to 20 lines per 100 people in urban areas by 2015,
said Jan Mutai, managing director of the Kenya Posts and
Telecommunications Corporation (KPTC).
</P>
<P>
"This works out to be an additional 300,000 lines for rural
areas and 2.4 million lines for urban areas," he said at a senior
seminar sidelined with the three-day show.
</P>
<P>
"The availability of an efficient and accessible
info-communication infrastructure is absolutely vital if the
country (Kenya) is to effectively compete in the emerging
information age and attain the status of a newly industrialized
country by the year 2020," said Mutai.
</P>
<P>
According to Mutai, demand for telecommunication services in
the country has consistently outstripped supply, leaving as many
as 80,000 Kenyans on the waiting list.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's tele-density now is less than one as compared to 9.2
lines per 100 people for South Africa while quality of service,
as measured by the number of faults per 100 main lines is above
100 as against 55 for the rest of the world, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he expected that the liberalization of the sector
set for later this year "would encourage inflow of private sector
capital to facilitate rapid roll-out of new telephone lines and
provide access to a telephone to all Kenyans."
</P>
<P>
Under two draft bills to be tabled in parliament earlier in
May, KPTC will be separated into Postal Corporation of Kenya and
Telkom Kenya Ltd. and the two new bodies will go public, sources
from the KPTC said at the show.
</P>
<P>
Foreign and private players will also be allowed to compete on
Kenya's telecommunication market then, said the sources, adding
that the nation's telecommunication services, whose efficiency
has been widely complained for years, would thus be greatly
improved.
</P>
<P>
A total of 35 exhibitors from Kenya, South Africa and Canada
participated in the show. They are suppliers of
telecommunication equipment, satellite and broadcast equipment,
networks, mobile cellular equipment, as well as service
providers.
</P>
<P>
The event serves as "a forum of information exchange to the
east Africans in order to effectively participate in the global
information and telecommunications market," said William Ntimama,
Kenyan Minister for Transport and Communications at the opening
ceremony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
