<HEADLINE> Yugoslavian Soldiers in Fire-fight With Kosovo Militants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavian armed forces
exchanged fire Wednesday night with more than 200 ethnic Albanian
militants near the border village of Kosara, a Yugoslavian
military source said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The conflict flared when Yugoslavian soldiers tried to bar the
militants' entry into Yugoslavia from neighboring Albania.
</P>
<P>
Both sides suffered casualties, said the source, but he didn't
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
The militants were believed to be ethnic Albanians from the
southern Serbian province of Kosovo, and had undergone military
training in a clandestine armed base in northern Albania, the
source said.
</P>
<P>
Tensions in Kosovo escalated since late February when conflict
erupted between Serb police and Kosovo's ethnic Albanians who were
seeking independence from Yugoslavia and integration into Albania.
</P>
<P>
Albania wanted Yugoslavian authorities to grant meaningful
autonomy to the Kosovo Albanians, who make up 90 percent of the
population in the province, and had hoped for the crisis to be
resolved peacefully. 
</P>
