<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Release of Kidnapped ICRC Staff Still Unresolved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The fate of the ten kidnapped
International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) staff still
remains unresolved Thursday, as it enters the ninth day since
they were taken into hostage.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday night, the abducted were for the first time
visited by officials from the Somali Red Crescent Society (SRCS)
and members of the ICRC in Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The SRCS and ICRC officials who spent about 15 minutes with
the hostages said they found them fine and well treated. The
officials told the abducted that they will be released later
Thursday or Friday at the latest.
</P>
<P>
The officials are currently holding a meeting with the
negotiators who seem to have concluded their attempt in unifying
the militiamen holding the ICRC staff who misunderstood over the
way and modalities of the release of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, it is known that the abductors will be offered some
money (between 60,000 and 150,000 US Dollars) under what is
termed as contribution from the clan business community, and no
ransom will be given so as to avoid other dangers from the
militiamen who might try to use the abduction of the
international expatriates as a revenue making business.
</P>
<P>
The latest information concerning the release efforts says all
the concerned parties seem to have understood each other and that
a conclusion is to be reached later Thursday or Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to members who attended the meeting, this time it is
even in a better situation which is different from the previous
hopes given to the public.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, since the danger is everywhere in the chaotic
Somalia, the area where the ICRC hostages are being kept is not
exceptional.  Early Thursday morning, a Russian made B-10
anti-tank gun discharged accidentally right beside the building
where the ten ICRC members are kept.
</P>
<P>
An eyewitness said the discharged round came from one of the
battle wagons responsible for the security of the hostages, while
the technical vehicle was patrolling the area.
</P>
<P>
The heavy round of the B-10 hit a large tree before it went
through a clinic nearby. Fortunately, no one was killed or
wounded because of the early hour, but it has terrorized the
people in the area including the ICRC hostages.
</P>
<P>
This abduction not only affects the humanitarian situation in
the country, but also hampers the reconciliation efforts
throughout the country as well as the on-going plan of the
establishment of Mogadishu's administration, which was scheduled
to be announced on the 16th of this month before the abduction
stood in its way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Deaths Reported In Collapsed Building In Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- A total of eight people who were
trapped in a building that collapsed in Changsha, the capital of
central China's Hunan Province, have been found dead, according to
local sources.
</P>
<P>
By 2:00 p.m.today, resue workers had dug out the last of the
victims from the rubble and announced that none of them survived
the accident. The victims were mostly female students from a
technical school who worked as interns in a garment company in the
building.
</P>
<P>
The upper three stories of the six-story building in the
downtown area collapsed without warning at around 5:00 p.m. on
Tuesday, trapping a dozen people, one of whom was confirmed dead
immediately afterwards.
</P>
<P>
Rescue workers saved six people on Tuesday and tunneled about
10 meters through the debris to pass water and food to the others
who were trapped in the rubble. The rescue proved very difficult
because of the narrow and cramped spaces.
</P>
<P>
A preliminary investigation has led investigators to believe
that the collapse was caused by the addition of one story to the
original five-story structure, sources say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
