<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Construction, Tourism Lifting Cambodian GDP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, April 23 (Xinhua) -- An increase in construction,
coupled with a slow recovery in tourism, could boost Cambodia's
gross domestic product by 3.5 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Keat Chhon told a book launching ceremony that
growth in construction and manufacturing is helping promote GDP
growth, which increased only two percent last year.
</P>
<P>
He said he expects the tourism industry to continue its slow
recovery this year, after the number of visitors plummeted last
year because the Asian economic meltdown coincided with factional
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
An economic crisis occurred in Thailand and then swept through
South-east Asia.
</P>
<P>
Last July saw the former First Prime Minister Prince Norodom
Ranariddh ousted by his co-premier, Hun Sen, in the wake of a
military conflict, which scared away visitors bringing tourism to
a halt.
</P>
<P>
Though optimistic about economic prospects, Keat Chhon warned
growth could be reduced due to problems in collecting logging and
customs revenues.
</P>
<P>
Revenues from logging funneled into the treasury are still far
below the Finance Ministry's projections, he said.
</P>
<P>
The treasury has collected only 370,000 U.S. dollars from
logging this year, as opposed to the projected 3.4 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund last year decided to leave its
office vacant in Phnom Penh. The body was frustrated by tax
exemptions for logging companies and the government's inability to
channel timber revenues to the national budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
