<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Writer Says More Popular Science Books In Chinese Needed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- An author of popular science
books in China said today that translators need to work on more
foreign books and articles on popular science.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Daoyi, the executive vice-chairman of the Chinese Science
Writers' Association (CSWA) board of directors, says that a large
number of books on popular science were translated from the late
1970s to the 1980s, but that the number has been dropping in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
He said that translations should be just as important as the
writing of popular science because many countries have published
better materials than China has.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 members of CSWA gathered in Beijing today to
discuss its plan for this year, which includes a popular science
translation contest and a collection of the world's popular
science classics.
</P>
<P>
CSWA is a non-government organization for popular science
writers, translators and critics. It has sponsored quite a few
popular science writing contests and held exhibitions of science
and fine arts in its twenty years. It has also been involved in
judging national scientific achievement awards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
