-- Americans are beginning to react against the government
policy of continued sanctions against Iraq by organizing their
own relief projects for the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
-- Nearly one in five doctors who care for seriously ill and
dying people reported that they had been asked for assistance in
speeding a patient's death, a report says in the intense debate
over physician-assisted suicide.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Federal officials and aviation groups, after months of
wrangling, have agreed to speed introduction of new equipment
and computer software to ease air-traffic congestion in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
-- Japan's senior financial official said Japan's economic
fundamentals are "relatively good," and warned that the yen's
recent weakness could reverse itself once the economic package
begins to boost the economy. 
</P>
