<HEADLINE> Sampras Loses in Monte Carlo Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Pete Sampras suffered an early
defeat in the third round of the 2.2 million U.S. dollars Monte
Carlo Open tennis tournament on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Sampras lost to Frenchman Fabrice Santoro 6-1, 6-1 in 66
minutes, but could still took over the No. 1 ranking this week
from Chilean Marcelo Rios who missed the event due to injury.
</P>
<P>
Plagued by unforced errors, Sampras looked little like the
player who beat Andre Agassi the day before, dropping six straight
games in the first set and lost his serve five of seven times in
the match against Santoro.
</P>
<P>
In the first set, Sampras held his first serve before lost six
straight games in a row as Santoro kept Sampras off-balance with
angled shots.
</P>
<P>
Santoro broke Sampras again for 3-1 and never looked back in
the second set until the final game where Sampras failed to
convert two break points.
</P>
<P>
On clay court, Santoro enjoyed upperhands against Sampras and
other big names, by beating Sampras at the Italian Open in 1991
and 1995, eliminating Thomas Muster and Sergi Bruguera at Monte
Carlo.
</P>
<P>
It was the third consecutive tournament that Sampras has lost
before the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
Petr Korda, with a slight chance to overtake Sampras for the
No. 1 ranking, played Albert Costa in another third-round match.
</P>
<P>
Marcelo Rios, currently No. 1, will drop out of the top spot
after missing this tournament that he won last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
