<HEADLINE> hke042367 -Patrick Gets Stay on Australian Federal Court Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Australia's High Court late
Thursday night granted stevedoring company's Patrick a stay in
Melbourne on Australia's Federal Court orders to reinstate the
1,400 Maritime Union of Australia (MUA) workers it sacked.
</P>
<P>
High Court Justice Ken Hayne froze the reinstatement of the
workers ahead of a formal application by Patrick for a stay on
Friday, the Australian Broadcasting Corporation radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Thursday night, a Full Bench of Australia's Federal
Court ruled an order in Melbourne reinstating 1,400 sacked Patrick
company's dock workers should be upheld, a move put the Australian
government and the company in a difficult position, but welcomed
by the union as a victory.
</P>
<P>
The victory was short-lived as Patrick, the nation's second
largest stevedoring company, sought the stay from the High Court,
the supreme court in Australia, pending a hearing for special
leave to appeal the Federal Court's orders.
</P>
<P>
MUA Sydney Branch Secretary Robert Coombs described the High
Court's stay ruling as a "delaying tactic" by Patrick.
</P>
<P>
He said the union was seeking legal advice on the decision to
determine its next move.
</P>
<P>
The legal battles were triggered by the April 7 mass sacking of
1,400 unionized workers by Patrick with the support of the
Australian government in a bid to break MUA's monopoly on the
nation's major ports.
</P>
<P>
The Australian government has indicated time and again that it
was determined to push ahead its waterfront reform.
</P>
<P>
In a speech made Thursday afternoon, Australian Prime Minister
John Howard reaffirmed his government's determination to reform
the Australian waterfront would remain undiminished, irrespective
of any court outcome.
</P>
<P>
Howard said court decisions "will come and go" but at the end
of the day it was the government's policy changes that would
deliver a more economic, reformed, productive and more competitive
Australian waterfront. 
</P>
</TEXT>
