timing is no problem for ARATS, Tang said. So long as the two
sides make proper arrangements, ARATS could invite mr. Koo anytime.
</P>
<P>
"We have already made sound preparations and hope the Taiwan
side could put forward more specific opinions," said Tang.
</P>
<P>
Prior to that meeting, Li Yafei, deputy-secretary general of
ARATS, exchanged views with Jan Jyh-horng on mr. Koo's visit to
the mainland. ARATS officials also listened to specific
suggestions from SEF on exchanges between the two organizations.
</P>
<P>
In order to help cross-straits relations, ARATS has sent four
letters to the SEF this year, suggesting that the two
organizations hold procedural talks on political negotiations, and
then make arrangement to resume talks on economic and other
affairs.
</P>
<P>
ARATS said it hopes the two organizations will increase
exchanges before the talks begin.
</P>
<P>
Jan and his party are scheduled to leave for Taiwan on Friday.
</P>
