<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reasons Behind Recent Ban on Direct Sales in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- People's Daily, the leading
national newspaper, carried an article today reviewing the
short-lived history of direct sales in China.
</P>
<P>
The State Council earlier this week issued a circular demanding
the halt of all direct sales activities before October 31, thus
ending a 10-year-old direct sales practice in China.
</P>
<P>
Direct sales has spread at an alarming speed in China after it
was first introduced into the country at the end of the 1980s. By
the end of 1995, 163 firms had begun practicing direct sales in
more than 30 major Chinese cities, the article says.
</P>
<P>
Taking advantage of a lack of legal regulations, many business
people and enterprises have waged excessive and false publicity
campaigns and lured consumers into buying excessively high-priced
commodities through direct sales.
</P>
<P>
For example, a Taiwanese jewelry firm registered in Harbin in
northeast China stipulated that only those who bought at least
10,000 yuan (1,204 U.S. dollars) worth of its jewelry can become
its direct sellers. Actually, the jewelry was worth only 3,000 to
4,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Lured by an illusion of staggering profit, 1,600 people
registered as direct sellers for the Taiwanese firm. However, only
933 of them received bonuses and recouped their investment in the
end.
</P>
<P>
According to the article, most of the direct sales firms have
relied on offering prices many times higher than the market price,
and many of the products directly sold proved to be fake or
substandard.
</P>
<P>
What is worse, a number of people have made use of direct sales
to engage in superstition as well as reactionary and underworld
gang activities.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government in recent years has launched three
special fights against direct sales activities. However,
the crackdowns have failed to address the fundamental problem.
</P>
<P>
"Due to immature market conditions, inadequate legislation and
immature consumer psychology, direct sales have proved
unsuitable for China and thus must be resolutely banned," the
article states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Sets 7 Percent Growth in Fifth Five-year Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's fifth five-year plan
(1997-2002) has fixed an annual average growth rate of 7 percent
for the country's economy, State Minister for Planning, Science
and Technology Mohiuddin Khan Alamgir said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The plan has projected the growth rate at 6 percent in the
first year of the five-year period and 8.3 percent in the last
year, Alamgir told reporters, unveiling the government's ambitious
plan, approved by the cabinet early last month.
</P>
<P>
To this end, some 1,960 billion taka (about 42.6 billion U.S.
dollars) will be invested both in the public and private sectors,
with 44 percent going to the public sector and the rest to the
private sector, he said.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-eight percent of the investment will come from domestic
sources, the state minister added.
</P>
<P>
The average per capita income during the five-year period will
increase at a rate of 5.5 percent annually, against the average
population growth rate of 1.37 percent a year, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"We have to achieve the average growth rate of 7 percent
through boosting growth in the agricultural, industrial and social
sectors," he said.
</P>
<P>
Some 16.46 percent of the total investment has been earmarked
for agriculture, 15.85 percent for industry, 13.5 percent for
transport and communication, and 13 percent for the energy sector,
according to Alamgir.
</P>
<P>
And the allocation for education and health has been fixed at
22 percent, against the 10.7 percent in the fourth five year plan.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
