<HEADLINE> Japanese Emperor Meets Chinese Vice-President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 23 (Xinhua)-- Emperor Akihito of Japan had a
cordial and friendly conversation with visiting Chinese
Vice-President Hu Jintao at the Imperial Palace here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Hu told the Emperor that he has exchanged views with Japanese
government leaders, and people from various sectors, on developing
a good-neighborly Sino-Japanese relationship towards the next
century, and has reached consensus on many issues.
</P>
<P>
Extending his welcome to Hu's Japan tour, Emperor Akihito said
Hu's visit had been fruitful following his meetings with Japanese
people from all walks of life. He hoped the development of
Sino-Japanese ties would continue.
</P>
<P>
Hu noted that great strides have been taken in developing
bilateral relations and that Sino-Japanese ties have entered a
period of inheriting the past and ushering in the future.
</P>
<P>
The enhancement of Sino-Japanese relations are of major
significance both to the interests of the two peoples and to
peace, stability and development in the Asia-Pacific region and
the entire world, Hu said.
</P>
<P>
Hu said China and Japan should take lessons from history and
work together to foster long-term, stable, good-neighborly and
cooperative ties oriented towards the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Noting the planned visit by Chinese President Jiang Zemin this
fall, Hu said it will be the first visit to Japan by a Chinese
president and will surely push forward bilateral friendly and
cooperative relations.
</P>
<P>
The Emperor recalled his China visit in 1992 which, he said,
had left him with a beautiful impression. He told Hu that he is
looking forward to meeting with Chinese President Jiang Zemin this
autumn in Tokyo. 
