<HEADLINE> The Two Koreas Exchange Weather Information </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Republic of Korea (ROK) and the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) Thursday exchanged
their first direct telegrams on weather-related information since
the Korean War in the early 1950s.
</P>
<P>
The ROK Meteorological Administration said it sent a telegram,
in the name of Seoul Kimpo Airport Office, to Pyongyang's Sunan
Airport at 11 a.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The telegram, written in English, appealed for the exchange of
weather information for various purposes, including ensuring
flight safety over DPRK territory.
</P>
<P>
It said the South and North sides should cooperate to reduce
weather-induced mishaps through exchanges of information and joint
research.
</P>
<P>
A reply telegram from the DPRK, sent around noon, said the
north side had received Seoul's telegram and wanted to know
whether there were any problems for flight operations.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK Thursday opened its sky for international flights,
including the ROK's national airliners.
</P>
<P>
The Southern administration said it will continue to provide
the DPRK with weather reports and warnings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
