<HEADLINE> Estrada Cleared Off Slay Plot Against Philippine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Department of
Justice Thursday cleared Vice President Joseph Estrada off the
allegations that he planned in 1992 the assassination of President
Fidel Ramos.
</P>
<P>
A five-man panel headed by Justice Undersecretary Jesus
Zozobrado said there were no sufficient evidences to charge
Estrada even if the allegations "are probably true".
</P>
<P>
Zozobrado said, even if the allegations of senior police
officer Reynaldo Berroya were true, they could not be made as a
basis for the filing of criminal complaint against Estrada.
</P>
<P>
"There were no evidences that Estrada had done any overt acts
to pursue the proposal, such as setting up money, buying of guns,
and organizing people for the purpose", Zozobrado said.
</P>
<P>
He added that another vital witness has already been dead, so
there could be no one to corroborate Berroya's allegations.
</P>
<P>
Berroya said earlier last month that Estrada planned to kill
Ramos in 1992 and smuggled some firearms into the country for the
purpose.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, presidential candidate of the opposition who has been
leading all surveys, said the charges were part of the ruling
party's black propaganda to stop him from winning the May 11
elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
