<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNITA Says It Can't Meet UN Deadline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The National Union for Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) said here Thursday that it can't
meet the United Nations deadline for reestablishing state organs
in areas still under its control.
</P>
<P>
Alcides Sakala, UNITA Secretary in charge of external
relations, said that the Angolan opposition movement can't meet
the deadline set by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan because
"necessary conditions are still lacking".
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Angola state radio, Sakala said that
conditions were still not ripe to meet the deadline set by the
U.N. Secretary-General and UNITA is still negotiating with the
Angolan government on issues concerning the reestablishment of
state authorities.
</P>
<P>
In his report on the Angolan peace process submitted to the
U.N. Security Council recently, Annan said that state authorities
should be reestablished by the end of April in Bailundo,
currently headquarters of UNITA, Andulo and other "sensitive
areas" controlled by the rebel movement.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief also asked UNITA to accomplish before the end
of this month all the suspending tasks stipulated in the 1994
Lusaka Peace Protocol.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA leader, however, stressed that what is important is
not to race against time but to go on with the negotiations so
that the remaining problems can be resolved at an appropriate
time.
</P>
<P>
According to the timetable agreed on March 6 by the Angolan
government and UNITA, the reestablishment of local governments in
Bailundo and Andulo should be completed by the end of March.
</P>
<P>
But the goal was not reached due to the delay by UNITA. The
peace process is now in a dilemma as the negotiations between the
two warring sides have born no fruits.
</P>
<P>
However, as was noted in Annan's report, 269 of the 335 cities
and towns controlled by UNITA across the southern African country
prior to the signing of the Lusaka Peace Protocol in 1994 have
already been returned to the Angolan government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
