<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stable Prices Seen in Next Two Months in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Stable prices for basic
commodities are projected in the next two months in the
Philippines given the lower oil prices in the local and world
markets, a senior official said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the president, Trade and Industry
Undersecretary Melito Salazar said the prices continue to be kept
at stable levels with "hardly any major fluctuations because of
adequacy in supply and rigid price monitoring activities done by
the local governments and concerned national government agencies."
</P>
<P>
The demand for agricultural and basic commodities would also
help maintain prices at generally stable levels, Salazar said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the price monitoring report of his department for
the third week of April showed general price stability of selected
basic commodities in specific urban centers nationwide.
</P>
<P>
"Prices of canned fish, milk, coffee, laundry soap, detergent
bars, common nail wire, cement, and steel bars are generally in
adequate supply," he said.
</P>
<P>
Salazar said the monitoring activities by government agencies
could greatly help the government achieve its single-digit
inflation target by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The country's inflation rate for March fell to 7.3 percent from
February's 7.4 percent, but it was much higher than last year's
average of 5.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, analysts said that food supplies were far from
enough in the drought-stricken southern Mindanao. It was reported
that at least 3.7 million people there have been affected by the
El Nino-induced drought and 64 of them had died in famine.
</P>
</TEXT>
