<HEADLINE> Australian Sacked Dock Workers Wins Critical Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- An Australian federal court
Thursday night ruled that an order in Melbourne reinstating 1,400
sacked Patrick company's dock workers should be upheld.
</P>
<P>
The decision, read by presiding Judge Murray Wilcox, was
broadcast live on Australian Broadcasting Corporation TV and
radio.
</P>
<P>
An ecstatic roar from the 2,000 dock workers gathered at the
picket at Melbourne's East Swanson Dock greeted the decision.
</P>
<P>
It remains to be seen that whether the government and the
company will accept the latest ruling and how long the 14-day-old
nationwide dispute would drag on.
</P>
<P>
The Australian government has indicated time and again that it
is determined to push ahead its waterfront reform, referring to
its plan to improve the productivity on the nation's ports by
breaking Maritime Union of Australia's monopoly over the nation's
major ports.
</P>
<P>
In a speech made Thursday afternoon well before the latest
ruling, Australian Prime Minister John Howard reaffirmed that his
government's determination to reform the Australian waterfront
would remain undiminished, irrespective of any court outcome.
</P>
<P>
Howard said court decisions "will come and go" but at the end
of the day it was the government's policy changes that would
deliver a more economic, reformed, productive and more competitive
Australian waterfront.
</P>
<P>
"The resolute belief of my government is that it is essential
we go into the 21st century with a modern, competitive waterfront,
irrespective of any particular decision in certain cases," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister made the comments earlier Thursday at Sydney
airport before leaving for Thailand for meetings with Thai
leaders.
</P>
<P>
Federal Court justice Tony North on Tuesday made the order to
give the dock workers their jobs back ahead of a trial on claims
that Patrick conspired unlawfully to sack them.
</P>
<P>
Patrick later appealed against the order to full bench of the
Federal Court, which rejected the appeal Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
John Edwards, an economist, predicted in a commentary on
financial markets Thursday afternoon that whatever the decision of
the court would be, the disruption to Australian trade from the
dispute could continue for some time to come. 
</P>
</TEXT>
