<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Consumer Price Indices Maintain Steady in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Consumer price inflation in
Hong Kong continued to be moderate in March, according to the
Consumer Price Index (CPI) figures for March released here today.
</P>
<P>
The figures, released by the Census and Statistics Department,
showed the year-on-year increase in the Composite CPI in March was
4.8 percent, following a 5.4 percent increase in January and 4.7
percent increase in February 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Composite CPI is compiled on the basis of the combined
expenditure pattern of households covered by three sub-indices.
CPI(A) covers about 50 percent of households with a monthly
expenditure of between 2,500 and 9,999 HK dollars. CPI(B) covers
about 30 of households with a monthly expenditure of between
10,000 and 17,499 HK dollars.
</P>
<P>
Comparing March with February, the Composite CPI increased by
0.3 percent. The corresponding increases for the CPI(A) and CPI(B)
were 0.1 percent and 0.3 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
For the first quarter of 1998, the increase in the Composite
CPI averaged at 5.0 percent over a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
For the 12-month ended March 1998, the Composite CPI was, on
average, higher by 5.6 percent than the preceding 12-month period.
</P>
<P>
The higher year-on-year rates of increase in the Composite CPI,
CPI(A) and CPI(B) in March than in February were mainly due to a
high base of comparison in February 1997 in respect of some fresh
food items and miscellaneous services. The increase in the charges
for electricity in March 1998 also contributed, according to the
department.
</P>
<P>
Analyzed by component, higher year-on-year rates of price
increase than the overall average in March were recorded for
housing, alcoholic drinks and tobacco.
</P>
<P>
Those components with lower year-on-year rates of price
increase than the overall average in March were fuel and light,
miscellaneous services and goods, clothing and footwear, and food.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
