<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
on Thursday approved the Agreement on Human Rights and
International Humanitarian Law recently initialed between the
government and the leftist rebel group, the National Democratic
Front (NDF).
</P>
<P>
The approval, announced by Executive Secretary Alexander
Aguirre, is seen to pave the way for a joint ceasefire agreement
for the duration of the on-going peace talks between the
government and the NDF, led by the Communist Party of the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will be implemented upon the declaration of a
mutual or joint suspension of armed hostilities for the duration
of the on-going peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Aguirre has relayed the qualified approval of the agreement to
NDF chairman Luis Jalandoni.
</P>
<P>
He also confirmed that the Department of Foreign Affairs is
expediting the passport of NDF leader Jose Ma. Sison for the
latter's return to the Philippines after more than 10 years of
self-exile in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Sison is expected to arrive in Manila before the end of this
month to witness the formal signing of the human rights agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Justice has issued a certification that Sison
has no pending criminal cases in courts for the speedy release of
his passport.
</P>
<P>
Aguirre again denied earlier NDF allegations that at present
there are still political prisoners in jail in the country.
</P>
<P>
"There is no such political prisoners, per se," he said,
"because all political prisoners have been released already."
</P>
<P>
The NDF has required the government to release about 143
political prisoners still in detention.
</P>
<P>
To build confidence with the NDF, Aguirre said the government
is conducting a review on this issue.
</P>
<P>
The New People's Army (NPA), the armed wing of the NDF, has
been waging a guerrilla warfare for the past 29 years. 
</P>
