<HEADLINE> Pak to Make Aid Request of 2.2b Dollars Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government is
considering to make an aid request for about 2.2 billion U.S.
dollars to the Pakistan Development Forum (PDF) during the 1998-99
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
According to a report Thursday by a major English Daily The
News, PDF, previously known as Aid-to-Pakistan Consortium, is
scheduled to meet in Islamabad from May 12 to 13.
</P>
<P>
A high level review mission of the International Monetary Fund
is also expected to take part in the two-day PDF session.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's aid request for the 1997-98 fiscal year was 2.2 68
billion dollars, comprising 2.066 billion dollars as project
assistance and 202 million dollars as quick disbursing commodity
aid.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted official sources as saying that the scheduled
session by PDF in May will be a non-pledging one. Main feature of
the proposed meeting will be the participation of private sector
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
The main items on the agenda of the meeting include good
governance, social sector development, particularly education and
energy sector developments.
</P>
<P>
The report said that given the increasingly constrained
international environment for official development assistance
after the cold war, its share of external funding is expected to
continue to decline gradually.
</P>
<P>
Most foreign financing of the balance of payments will have to
come from private commercial sources.
</P>
<P>
In this context, the perceived higher country risk, the reduced
credibility of economic policy in the light of the past experience
and the recent economic crisis in the region have adversely
affected Pakistan's access to international capital market.
</P>
</TEXT>
