<HEADLINE> E.U. Reopens Med' Cooperation Programs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The European Union is to reopen
its decentralized cooperation system in the Mediterranean region,
a move to advance Euro-Mediterranean relations.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the executive body of the E.U.,
decided Thursday to re-launch the program, known as the Med
Programs, to facilitate cooperation between representatives of
civil societies, an important element in Euro-Mediterranean
relations.
</P>
<P>
Focus will be on improving urban living conditions,
coordinating exchanges of experiences and know-how among
universities in the Mediterranean region, and developing networks
among the mass media.
</P>
<P>
A technical assistance office will be set up to examine the
implementation of the new program.
</P>
<P>
The programs were suspended in 1996 for checking and improving
the management systems, and for an in-depth technical and
financial evaluation by the commission.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation was re-launched with new management systems and
control measures in place following the recommendations of the
European Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Between 1992 and 1995, more than 470 networks were created,
bringing together about 2,000 partners from civil organizations
through these programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
