<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO to Launch Tourism Development Plan for India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The World Tourism Organization
(WTO) is to launch a tourism development plan for India focusing
on regional planning for areas identified by the Indian
government.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 36th meeting of the WTO commission for South
Asia and pan Asia/Pacific technical seminars in Kochi city of
Kerala State in the far southwestern India on Thursday, WTO Deputy
Secretary General Dawid J. De Villiers said that the plan to be
launched this year aimed at furthering human resource development
for the tourism sector.
</P>
<P>
India's potential in tourism was yet to be fully realized. in
1997, 2.37 million foreign tourists came to India, a growth of 3.8
percent over 1996. Similarly, tourist receipts exceeded 3.1
billion U.S. dollars, a growth of 6.5 percent over 1996, he said.
</P>
<P>
Indian Union Minister for Tourism Madan Lal Khurana said that
both the private and public sectors should cooperate to create
tourism infrastructure in India. One of the major pitfalls in the
country's tourism policy had been non-recognition of the
importance of public participation in tourism development.
</P>
<P>
In order to bridge critical infrastructural gaps like roads,
drainage and water supply systems in the identified tourist
centers, it was proposed to set up a tourism development fund, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The government would come out with a new pragmatic tourism
policy aimed at putting India on the global tourism map and a
policy to this end would be finalized within the next two months,
he further said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
