<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Observatory Planned for Yunnan Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Academy of Sciences
(CAS) plans to build a new astronomical observatory in Gaomeigu,
Lijiang Prefecture in southwest China's Yunnan Province, an area
considered to be the best location in south China for astronomical
observation.
</P>
<P>
The observatory will be built on Nantiejia Mountain in
northwest Yunnan. The facility, which will be located at an
elevation of 3,000 meters above the sea level, will enjoy clear
dark nights free of the lighting, pollution and dust
characteristic of cities, according to Wang Shouguan, a CAS
academician and member of the academy's site appraisal committee.
</P>
<P>
He said to definite of "seeing", a term astronomers use to
describe the clarity and steadiness of the atmosphere, clearly
ranks Gaomeigu as the best of five potential sites in the province.
</P>
<P>
Gaomeigu also offers better conditions for transportation and
other construction activities, said Wang.
</P>
<P>
CAS plans to install a two-meter telescope in the new
observatory, with the possibility for larger telescopes if
observation proves fruitful.
</P>
<P>
China recruited a large number of scientists to select
locations for new observatories in the 1960s, with CAS scientists
focusing their attention on Yunnan and finally selecting Gaomeigu
as an ideal location in 1992.
</P>
<P>
An observatory in a southern province will provide more chances
for astronomical observation in general since China is in the
Northern Hemisphere, according to Wang.
</P>
<P>
The fact that observatories in Beijing, Nanjing, Shanghai,
Xi'an and Kunming must deal with light and air pollution in
surrounding areas prompted Chinese astronomers to search for
better locations, said Wang.
</P>
<P>
The Nanjing Zijinshan Observatory's satellite station in
northwest China's Qinghai Province offers excellent "seeing"
quality.
</P>
<P>
The largest optical telescope in China is the 2.16-meter
telescope in the Xinglong Station operated by the Beijing
Astronomical Observatory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
