<HEADLINE> PNG's PM Offers to Meet Rebel Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Papua New Guinea (PNG) Prime
Minister Bill Skate Thursday offered to meet the disaffected
leader of Bougainville's secessionist rebels, Francis Ona, in a
bid to ensure the signing of a permanent ceasefire on the
war-ravaged island, Australian media reported.
</P>
<P>
In a blow to the current peace process, Ona last week demanded
an indefinite postponement of the ceasefire due to be signed by
the warring parties at Arawa in central Bougainville next
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Efforts have been made by all sides to involve Ona in bringing
peace to the Pacific island which has suffered a decade of
bloodshed under the secessionist rebellion.
</P>
<P>
In a conciliatory gesture, the prime minister said Thursday
that Ona was still the chief of Bougainville and added that there
were reports that the rebel chief wanted to meet him.
</P>
<P>
"The invitation is there... If he wants to meet with me I'd
love to meet with him," Skate was quoted by the Australian
Associated Press as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister said he remained confident that the
ceasefire agreement would still be signed next week.
</P>
<P>
A delegation of four Bougainvillean MPs in the PNG national
government is due to meet Ona on Monday in an 11th hour bid to
convince him to join the peace process, the wire service said.
</P>
<P>
The island rebels' struggle to gain independence from Papua New
Guinea has led to an estimated 15,000 deaths. 
</P>
</TEXT>
