<HEADLINE> Kuala Lumpur Stocks Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Share prices on the Kuala
Lumpur Stock Exchange closed higher Thursday on foreign buying of
key bluechips after sentiment was buoyant over the conclusion of
the financing for the RHB-Sime Bank merger.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said news of the RHB funding of the purchase of Sime
Bank triggered a realistic technical rebound after the market was
deprived of supportive leads to help push trade for the past two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
At the close, the 100-quality stocks Composite Index gained
8.57 points to 628.24, the all-share Emas Index added 1.04 points
to 158.46, the Industrial Index was 4.68 points higher at 1,154.82
while the Second Board Index eased 3.06 points to 138.71.
</P>
<P>
Gainers outpaced losers by 335 to 236 while 184 counters were
unchanged and 160 untraded.
</P>
<P>
The day's turnover was 115.816 million shares valued at 264.846
million ringgit (about 70.4377 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The main board volume rose to 104.928 million shares valued at
249.482 million ringgit (about 66.3515 million U.S. dollars) from
91.064 million shares worth 244.964 million ringgit (about 65.15
million U.S. dollars) Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The second board turnover increased marginally to 10.888
million shares valued at 15.364 million ringgit (about 4.0861
million U.S. dollars) from Wednesday's 10.419 million shares worth
17.607 million ringgit (about 4.6827 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Off-market deals shrank to 3.376 million shares valued at
12.272 million ringgit (about 3.2638 million U.S. dollars) from
4.580 million shares worth 19.310 million ringgit (about 5.1356
million U.S. dollars) on Wednesday. 
</P>
