<HEADLINE> Nhiek Bun Chhay Denies Relations With Khmer Rouge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, April 23 (Xinhua) -- General Nhiek Bun Chhay of
Cambodia Thursday denied any relations with the Khmer Rouge in
Anlong Veng.
</P>
<P>
Nhiek Bun Chhay, who is leading the forces loyal to Prince
Ranariddh, made the remarks in a three-point statement signed by
him in O'smach, an area near the Thai border controlled by the
Royal Cambodian Armed Forces (RCAF).
</P>
<P>
Rejecting rumors that he had relations with the Khmer Rouge, he
said, some Khmer Rouge units in Anlong Veng came over to surrender
to the RCAF.
</P>
<P>
But for the time being he had not made any decision on the
matter.
</P>
<P>
He also rejected the VOA April 22 report that picked up news
from the Thai TV saying the Khmer Rouge forces had merged with his
and had appointed Ta Mok as his advisor.
</P>
<P>
The truth was that he could only welcome the Khmer Rouge
defectors once they cut all their links with their leaders who
committed genocide, he added.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that he himself and all the other high ranking
commanders were part of the RCAF. Therefore, to avoid any further
accusation of having link with the Khmer Rouge, he proposed that
the United Nations send observers to verify and monitor the
situation on the spot.
</P>
<P>
Nhiek Bun Chhay, former deputy chief of RCAF general staff,
along with Prince Ranariddh, was tried by the Phnom Penh Military
Court on March 4 and 18. He was sentenced to 24 years in prison on
charges of conspiring with the Khmer Rouge to overthrow the
government, and has not been granted royal pardon yet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
