<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Reports 28 Percent Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, April 22 (Xinhua)-- Microsoft Corp., the world's
largest maker of personal computer software, reported Wednesday
that its fiscal third-quarter profits rose 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
Greg Maffei, chief financial officer of the company, said
Microsoft earned 1.34 billion dollars in the January-March
quarter, compared 1.04 billion dollars during the same period of
last year.
</P>
<P>
Revenue rose 18 percent to 3.77 billion dollars from 3.21
billion dollars, he added, saying the company was pleased that
consumer demand remained high for its products.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft said its profit margins rose in the quarter due to
relatively lower marketing expenses and a decline in research and
development costs.
</P>
<P>
Revenue from computer manufacturers that pre-install Microsoft
products on new computers rose to 1.23 billion dollars, an increase
of 28 percent over the year-earlier period, due to rising personal
computer sales and increased penetration of the costlier Windows
NT system.
</P>
<P>
"But it is critical to note that our growth has slowed for each
of the last four quarters, and we are likely to experience slower
growth for the balance of calendar 1998," Maffei said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts expect at least a modest boost from the release of the
Windows 98 operating system scheduled on June 25, and a major wave
of buying after the company releases its high-end Windows NT 5.0
operating system late this year or early 1999.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft operating systems run on more than 90 percent of
personal computers worldwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
