<HEADLINE> Iran Protests Killing of Shiite Leader in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Foreign Ministry on
Thursday summoned Iraqi charge d'affaires Salah Noori Samarmad
here to protest the killing of a famous Shiite Muslim leader in
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
According to the Tehran Radio, the ministry's director general
for Persian Gulf affairs demanded Iraqi government give necessary
explanation for the murder of Ayatollah Ali Mohammad Ibrahem
al-Boroujerdi in the Shiite holy city of Najaf in southern Iraq
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ayatollah Boroujerdi, the prayer leader at the shrine of Imam
Ali, who is respected by Shiites as the first successor of Islamic
Prophet Mohammed, was beaten to death by a group of unidentified
people, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
But an Iraqi announcement earlier said the Iranian sheikh was
shot to death when he was heading for home after praying at the
holy shrine of Imam Ali.
</P>
<P>
The announcement said the murderer escaped from the scene, and
accused "foreign intelligence" of being behind the assassination
because of the "religious belief and moderate attitude" of the
influential figure.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Foreign Ministry urged Iraqi government to arrest
and punish those responsible for killing.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi envoy expressed regret over the incident, promising
to inform his government of Iran's views and stance towards the
killing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
