<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Financial System Works Well, Review Shows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 23 (Xinhua) -- A review of Hong Kong financial
market demonstrated that the linked exchange rate mechanism has
been functioning well, the financial system has been sound and the
securities and futures markets have been operating orderly, a
leading Hong Kong financial official said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The administration has taken a thorough look at the operation
of the currency defense mechanism as well as the operation of the
financial markets in wake of speculators' attack against Hong Kong
dollar last October, which brought about a plunge in stock and
property prices.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference concerning a report on the review,
Financial Secretary Donald Tsang said, the local financial
community, academics both in and beyond Hong Kong as well as
experts from the International Monetary Fund were consulted during
the review period.
</P>
<P>
And the review has been premised on two fundamental principles.
</P>
<P>
"First, consistent with the mandate in the Basic Law, and
bearing in mind the long-term interest of Hong Kong as an open and
externally-oriented economy, we must maintain and enhance the
status of Hong Kong as an international financial
center. Secondly, consistent with the objective of maintaining the
stability of the Hong Kong dollar, the linked exchange rate
system which has served Hong Kong well must be preserved," Tsang
said.
</P>
<P>
The report pointed out that, despite the pain that has been
inflicted on the economy by the interest rate hike and asset price
adjustments, "the defense mechanism for the currency has very
effectively preserved the stability of the exchange rate and the
monetary system."
</P>
<P>
"The prudential regulatory framework for both the banking and
the securities sectors which we have carefully built up over the
years have formed effective buffers against the recent shocks," it
added.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's performance during the regional financial turmoil
should be granted an "A" mark, the official observed.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out, the government has identified a number
of areas where improvements can be made. "Some of the measures,
such as fixed-rate mortgages offering an additional financing
option for home buyers, have already been put in place," he said.
</P>
<P>
The report made a few recommendations concerning the stock
market, the futures and derivative markets, market surveillance
and risk management, market transparency, and investor protection
and education. For example, drawing a lesson from the failure of C
A Pacific, it recommended that broker-related finance companies
be subject to regulation by the Securities and Futures
Commission.
</P>
<P>
Secretary for Financial Services Rafael Hui, Chief Executive of
the Hong Kong Monetary Authority Joseph Yam and Chairman of the
Securities and Futures Commission Anthony Neoh joined Tsang in
attending the press conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
