<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spokesman on Failure of U.S. Motion Against Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- China welcomes the fact that the
United Nations Commission on Human Rights has rejected a
U.S. motion against Cuba, Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao
said here today.
</P>
<P>
The rejection was the first for a U.S.-sponsored anti-Cuba
resolution since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Zhu told reporters at today's regularly scheduled press
conference that the vote tally stood at 19 against, 16 for and 18
abstentions. He said China maintains that a country has the right
to decide how to promote and protect human rights in accordance
with its actual internal conditions.
</P>
<P>
China firmly opposes use of human rights issues to engage in
political confrontations, said Zhu, adding that an increasing
number of countries have voiced support the stand.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that Cuba has obtained increased support from members
of the U.N. Human Rights Commission proves the point once again,"
said Zhu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
