<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique to Shut Makeshift Cholera Clinics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican health authority has
decided to close the Makeshift tents for cholera patients in
Maputo City and Maputo Province as the epidemic situation becomes
stable.
</P>
<P>
The tents were set up to house patients as there were no more
beds in the Central Hospital of Maputo to treat cholera patients
but those in other areas, particularly in the central provinces
of Zambezia and Sofala will remain open, the Noticias newspaper
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted sources from the health administration
authority as saying that new cholera patients can go to the
Central Hospital of Maputo for treatment at present.
</P>
<P>
Until early this year, the Central Hospital of Maputo had been
the only hospital accepting cholera sufferers, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
As cholera broke out last August, there were so many patients
suffering from the epidemic that many tents had been set up as
makeshift clinics in the suburbs of the capital city and in the
province of Maputo in a bid to ease the pressure on the Central
Hospital of Maputo.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the medical staff working in these
clinics would return to their former posts and the students
invited to help would go back to the nurse schools to go on with
their study.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Director Assistant of the National Health
Administration Avertino Barreto reminded that cholera should not
be treated slightly in other areas, especially in the two
provinces of Zambezia and Sofala.
</P>
<P>
He said that 721 and 352 cholera cases occurred last week in
Zambezia and Sofala respectively, including 25 deaths in the
former.
</P>
<P>
Barreto warned the communities against a comeback of cholera
and asked them to pay attention to personal hygiene and the
sanitation of their surrounding environment.
</P>
<P>
So far, cholera has hit seven of the 10 provinces in
Mozambique. About 30,000 people have contracted the disease,
resulting in 720 dead.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Mozambican Treasury Ministry had again
appropriated 30 billion Meticais (some three million U.S.
Dollars) to help prevent and wipe out cholera and other epidemic
diseases in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
