<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Accelerates Construction of Yangtze Transport Routes (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- China is accelerating the pace of
construction on a number of key transportation routes along the
Yangtze River, the nation's longest river.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Railway's long-term plan for 1998-2020 calls
for the construction of a national railway network consisting of
four vertical and four horizontal lines. One line will run
parallel with the Yangtze from Chengdu and Chongqing to Nanjing
and Shanghai, via Daxian, Wanxian, Enshi, Wuhan and Jiujiang.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the Chengdu-Daxian and Wuchang-Jiujiang
sections has been completed, with work continuing on the
Shanghai-Nanjing-Tongling and Daxian-Wanxian sections. The design
phase of the Wanxian-Zhicheng section is also complete, and
construction of the Jingmen-Wuhan and Jiujiang-Tongling sections
will proceed between 1998-2002, according to a source from the
Ministry of Railways.
</P>
<P>
A national highway, which is scheduled to open around the year
2000, will link major cities along the Yangtze, including Chengdu,
Chongqing, Wanxian, Wuhan, Hefei, Nanjing, and Shanghai, according
to the Ministry of Communications which is in charge of
constructing and administering highways and water routes.
</P>
<P>
The Chengdu-Chongqing, Yichang-Huangshi, Hefei-Nanjing and
Nanjing-Shanghai expressways are currently under
construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
