<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier Qian Qichen Meets Portuguese Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier Qian Qichen and
Portuguese Foreign Minister Jaime Gama met today and pointed to
the success of this week's visit by a Portuguese delegation
led by Prime Minister Antonio Guterres.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that Portuguese President Jorge Sampaio's visit to
China in February last year promoted the development of
Sino-Portuguese ties. He also noted the continuing sound momentum
in the development of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
"We are delighted that Foreign Minister Gama is visiting China
after last year's visit by President Sampaio," said Qian.
</P>
<P>
Developing long-term stable, friendly and cooperative ties
based on mutual respect, equality and benefits not only conforms
to the fundamental interests of the two countries, but will also
promote the formation of a new European-Asian partnership.
</P>
<P>
Gama said the Portuguese media has praised the Prime Minister's
China tour, and noted that the visit will create a favorable
atmosphere for the further development of bilateral relations and
solving the Macao issue.
</P>
<P>
Qian briefed the visiting delegation on Chinese government
principles and policies concerning the resumption of China's
sovereignty over Macao.
</P>
<P>
He said China will pursue the principles of "one country, two
systems," "Macao people governing Macao," and a high degree of
autonomy in Macao.
</P>
<P>
Qian reaffirmed that the Chinese government will as always
abide by the Sino-Portuguese Joint Statement and will ensure the
smooth transition and handover of power in Macao.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have cooperated in accordance with the Joint
Statement and have effectively solved a number of problems, said
Qian, adding that the two sides should expand cooperation and
resolve all major issues concerning the handover in order to realize
the smooth transition of Macao.
</P>
<P>
This will benefit efforts to maintain stability and development
in Macao and will also conform to the common interests of the two
sides.
</P>
<P>
Gama said his government has adopted measures to ensure the
smooth transition and expressed hope that the joint liaison group
will accelerate its work in order to make progress in handling
all major issues related to the handover.  
</P>
</TEXT>
