<HEADLINE> Taiwan Authorities Criticized for Remarks on Bankrolling Southeast Asia  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Taiwan authorities have political
motives in their attempt to link themselves with the central
government to help Southeast Asian countries overcome their
financial difficulties and boost their economies, according to a
commentator's article today.
</P>
<P>
Through such a scheme, the article signed by Chen Binhua notes,
Taiwan is trying to take advantage of the temporary economic
difficulties of the countries in a bid to seek political benefits
and create recognition of "two Chinas" or "one China, one Taiwan."
</P>
<P>
The central government does not object to Taiwan's
non-governmental economic and trade exchanges with Southeast Asian
countries. Taiwan has close ties with those countries. However,
Taiwan has been acting in the way of hitting a person when he is
down in the middle of the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan has a huge foreign trade surplus, and its foreign
exchange reserves rank it third in the world. But the Taiwan
authorities have devaluated its currency, which affected the Hong
Kong stock market.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the Chinese government has been paying attention to
good-neighbor relations with Southeast Asian countries, and has
provided timely and strong assistance to some countries which
suffered from the financial disturbance.
</P>
<P>
What's more important, the Chinese government is striving not
to devalue the Renminbi in order to prevent even bigger financial
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Taiwan authorities, who hold the unshirkable
responsibility for worsening the financial crisis, want to be seen
as a savior. If it really cared for the difficulty of those
countries, the Taiwan authorities would not devaluate its currency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
