<HEADLINE> Bad Year Seen for Banking in Kenya: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan banks face a difficult
year in 1998, with profits undermined by a growing mountain of
non-performing loans, the East African Standard Thursday quoted
analysts as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The honeymoon is over for banks in this country," said Amish
Gupta, associate director of Shah, Munge &AMP; Partners, "Profits
will be flat."
</P>
<P>
Asset quality deteriorated last year with the proportion of
non-performing loans to total advances increasing by three
percentage points to 21 percent, the Central Bank of Kenya said
in its March month review.
</P>
<P>
Non-performing loans totaled 43.8 billion Shillings (735
million U.S. Dollars) at the end of December from an overall 209
billion Shillings in loans and advances, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Analysts estimate non-performing loans represent 8.6 percent
of Kenya's gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
"It is striking that the Kenyan banking system's level of
non-performing loans and advances is on the rise," said Gupta.
</P>
<P>
"It is deteriorating precariously close to other emerging
markets that have already undergone serious banking crises which
were very expensive," he said.
</P>
<P>
Latest data from Standard Chartered Bank show non-performing
loans shot up to 458 million Shillings in 1997 from 47.2 million
Shillings in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Barclays Bank of Kenya results for the same period show bad
debts rose to 222 million Shillings from 72 million Shillings in
1996. Barclays noted that 1997 was an exceptionally bad year for
non-performing loans.
</P>
<P>
"We made a net specific provision... to take account mainly of
four large lendings whose recovery became doubtful," Samuel
Ambundo, the bank's chairman said.
</P>
<P>
He said this despite interest rates of 30-to-40 percent,
caused by high government borrowing through treasury bills. The
high rates are in turn the main reason for the bad loans problem,
analysts say.
</P>
<P>
Poor supervision of lending is another factor behind defaults.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the government fired three directors, the general
manager and the executive chairman of Kenya Commercial Bank, the
country's largest bank, after newspapers reported the directors
and general manager had allowed irregular and unsecured loans.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say commercial banks will struggle to recover the bad
debts currently on their books. But non-performing loans are
unlikely to increase much further because banks are not lending
much money privately.
</P>
<P>
With interest rates on three-month treasury bills around 27
percent, analysts say banks have found it more profitable to lend
to the government in the last nine months, at the expense of
ordinary Kenyans.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Finance Minister Simeon Nyachae warned Wednesday that
the country's economic situation was becoming uncontrollable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Authorities Criticized for Remarks on Bankrolling Southeast Asia  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Although the Taiwan authorities have said time and again that
it does not have any political goal advocating joint efforts with
the mainland, an editorial carried by the Central Daily News of
Taiwan expressed the hope that the mainland should make two
breakthroughs: not to force the Renminbi to retain its value and
not adhere to the traditional concept on sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
In this sense, the advocacy clearly shows that the Taiwan
authorities aim to split the motherland, and does not really
intend to relieve the difficulties of Southeast Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
The central government has been adhering to the eight-point
proposal set forth by President Jiang Zemin on developing the
relations across the Taiwan Straits and promoting the
reunification of the motherland. And it has been showing sincerity
and flexibility to improve relations.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, the Taiwan authorities not only obstinately hold
out-of-date views, but also raise new issues hindering the proper
development of cross-Straits relations.
</P>
<P>
The masses of compatriots in Taiwan, especial the figures in
the industrial and business circles, have been calling for direct
shipping, mail and business links between the two sides, only to
be met by indolence on the part of Taiwan authorities. But, on the
other hand, it pretends to be active in assisting Southeast Asian
countries along with the mainland.
</P>
<P>
The advocacy of joining hands with the mainland has inevitably
met objections from the central government. In fact, the Central
Daily News pointed out in an editorial that the mainland would not
accept such an advocacy.
</P>
<P>
What the Taiwan authorities do is aimed at making up for its
bad image in delaying cross-Straits political talks and cashing in
on the financial crisis in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
As the Association for Relations Across the Taiwan Straits
(ARATS) recently invited the deputy secretary general of the
Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF) of Taiwan to the mainland to
exchange views on the proposed mainland tour of SEF Chairman Koo
Chen-fu, the relations across the straits has been inclining to
ease. This has drawn an extensive welcome from the people of
Chinese origin around the world as well as from the international
community, the article says. Moreover, it adds, "We hope that the
Taiwan authorities take positive measures in response to the
mainland's call for political talks instead of going in for
unrealistic "substantial diplomacy."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
