<HEADLINE> Philippine Light Rail Workers Stage Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Some 100 workers of the
Philippines' Light Rail Transit Trains (LRT) launched a strike
over wage issues Thursday, stranding hundreds of commuters in
metro Manila and nearby suburbs.
</P>
<P>
The LRT is supposed to begin regular operation at 5:00 a.m.,
but because of the strike called by the LRT labor union, the
trains did not operate Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Sammy Malones, spokesman of the LRT's striking workers, said
they blocked all gates of LRT's stations in the whole metro Manila
to protest against the employers' non-compliance with the
collective bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
The striking workers are demanding for a 3,500-peso
across-the-board increase in salaries for this year and 3,000
pesos for 1999. They are also seeking a general increase in other
benefits and improvement of working conditions.
</P>
<P>
But Malones said their employers only approved a salary
increase of 1,000 pesos.
</P>
<P>
Moises Tolentino, LRT general manager, said the management will
file a petition for injunction with the labor department to order
the workers to go back to work and declare that the strike is
illegal.
</P>
<P>
If the labor department will order the break-up of the strike,
"the LRT is ready to operate the trains even if the strikers
continue their action outside our premises," Tolentino said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
