<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Two and a half months after the prefect of Corsica Claude
Erignac was assassinated, police are now convinced that the attack
was inscribed in a inner power struggle of the hardline branch of
separatist group FLNC, the FLNC-Canal historique. Police are afraid
that new attacks would come soon.
</P>
<P>
-- During a hearing of the National Assembly information
commission on Rwanda on Wednesday, the son of President
Francois-Mitterrand, Jean-Christophe Mitterrand, denied any dubious
role played by his father in the 1994 genocide in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Christophe, who was the advisor for African affairs for his
father for eight years, also denied that he had personal relations
with the son of former Rwandan President Juvenal Habyramina and
charges that he had run a marijuana business in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- In an interview with Le Figaro, the president of the
Elf-Aquitaine oil group Philippe Jaffre said in 10 years, his
group will be among one of the 10 best in the world in all its
trades and one of the 50 top enterprises in the world. He also
called for "a profound change of the strategy, culture and
organization" of Elf after the departure of his predecessor, Loik
Le Floch-Prigent.
</P>
<P>
-- An inter-ministerial commission in charge of investigating the
problem of sects in France has submitted its first report to Prime
Minister Lionel Jospin. The government could draft new laws to
intensify the fight against sects and submit them to the National
Assembly for approval. 
</P>
</TEXT>
