<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Accelerates Construction of Yangtze Transport Routes (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Yangtze, which meanders 6,300 km. through east China,
has grown into a major water transportation channel featuring
numerous high capacity ports. Completion of the massive Three
Gorges Project will enable vessels rated at 10,000 tons to reach
Chongqing in the upper reaches of the river.
</P>
<P>
Water transportation offers a number advantages over other
forms of transport, including high capacity, low costs and low
energy consumption as well as no demand for the use arable
land. Experts point out that full development of the Yangtze's
cargo transport capacity would equal the total volume for 14
parallel railway lines.
</P>
<P>
The Chengdu-Shanghai air route via Chongqing, Wuhan and Nanjing
is one of the busiest routes in the country.
</P>
<P>
The capacity of the route continues to grow along with
construction of Chengdu's Shuangliu Airport, the Tianhe Airport in
Wuhan, Lukou Airport in Nanjing and Pudong Airport in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze passes through economically disadvantaged
southwestern and central regions which the central government has
listed for key development projects, as well as the developed
Yangtze River Delta in the lower reaches of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the transport routes will enable the areas
share natural and technological resources, in addition to making
full use of their unique advantages, expanding tourism and creating
conditions for the continuance of China's high economic growth
rate, according to economists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
