<HEADLINE> Arabs Concerned with Turkey-Jordan Military Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The rapidly growing military ties
between Turkey and Jordan have prompted serious concern among some
Arab countries, the Daily News reported here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Senior Arab diplomats in Ankara were quoted by the paper as
saying that Arab countries are closely watching the continuing
development of military cooperation between Turkey and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
An Arab ambassador, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
that Turkey, together with Israel, are trying to win over Jordan
and include it into their military alliance.
</P>
<P>
"They are trying to pull Jordan into these arrangements," he
told the paper. Turkey and Israel have concluded two deals to
enhance military cooperation in defiance of outcry from the Arab
world.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, who signed peace with Israel in 1994, is feared by some
Arab countries of being lured into the Turkey-Israel fold, which
is considered a threat to the Arab nation.
</P>
<P>
Jordan sent a high-ranking observer to a joint naval maneuver
of Turkey, Israel and the United States in January in eastern
Mediterranean. Arab countries were opposed to the war games.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Embassy officials in Ankara declined to comment on
the reported Arab concern.
</P>
<P>
Local reports have said that Jordan and Turkey exchanged troops
early this week for joint training aimed at enhancing coordinated
capabilities of the two armies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
