<HEADLINE> Australian PM Leaves for Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister John Howard left
Australia Thursday afternoon for a three-day visit to Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Howard is due to meet his counterpart Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai and Thai cabinet ministers and witness the signing of
agreements during his visit.
</P>
<P>
He also will attend the opening ceremony of the Hellfire Pass
memorial museum and other ceremonies at the bridge on River Kwai.
</P>
<P>
"The museum was constructed in one of the most notorious and
sacred spots in which Australian servicemen were involved in the
construction of the Burma-Thailand railway during World War II and
where so many hundreds of lives were lost," he told reporters
before leaving.
</P>
<P>
"It is a very fitting memorial to one of the most remembered
and tragic chapters in Australian military history," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a high-level business mission, including 14 business
executives is accompanying the prime minister for the visit.
</P>
<P>
The business leaders will hear briefings by the Thai foreign
minister and experts.
</P>
<P>
There will also be a macro-economic overview from the assistant
governor of the Bank of Thailand and a briefing on opportunities
for Australian investors in the asset disposal of 56 financial
companies from Thai finance minister. 
