<HEADLINE> China Scores Progress in Information Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 23 (Xinhua) -- "China's information industry
has witnessed four notable achievements as humanity treads on the
threshold of a new information era," according to Lu Xinhui,
vice-minister of Information Industry.
</P>
<P>
Lu made the remark during the ongoing two-day '98 International
Electronic Business Forum which opened yesterday in Shanghai. Lu
said that China initiated a series of programs in the early 1990s
to spread applications of electronic information technologies
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
The national securities information network has assimilated
information on over 300 securities companies and 2,600 affiliates
since 1994. The highest daily turnover for some 39.8 million
investors in China's securities market reached 30 billion yuan,
said Lu.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that China's automatic account settlement
network is linked by over 600 ground satellite stations and 1,000
receiving stations. The network, which covers all city-level
administrations and 700 counties, handled an average of between
50,000-60,000 transactions daily.
</P>
<P>
Lu added that the nation's airline ticket reservation system
has been in operation for 12 years, with some 55.6 million tickets
valued at 20 billion yuan booked in 1997 alone.
</P>
<P>
China had issued 50.56 million credit cards by the end of last
year, said Lu.
</P>
<P>
He said that a variety of electronic information systems
covering wide-ranging areas, including ocean shipping, commodities
trading and ordering, are playing an increasingly important role
in accelerating China's import and export sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
