<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 09:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel-Turkey Deal on Anti-Missile System Denied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Israel has denied reports that
it signed a memorandum of understanding with Turkey on jointly
developing an anti-ballistic missile defense system, the Jerusalem
Post reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Israeli government officials as saying that
the two countries did discuss the possibility of cooperation on
developing the defense system during an annual defense meeting
held in Ankara last month.
</P>
<P>
But they said no agreement was signed at the meeting. Turkey
prefers to wait until the Israeli prototype Arrow system, which
is making significant progress, is completed and deployed, they
added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier press reports said that the two sides inked a deal in
March to study the feasibility of developing a Turkish defense
program modeled after the Arrow anti-missile system, which has
been largely financed by Washington since 1988.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of Defense William Cohen reportedly discussed
the Israeli-Turkish collaboration with his Israeli counterpart
Yitzhak Mordechai during his lastest visit here last Monday.
</P>
<P>
Ankara has been closely following the Arrow program while
expressing interests in obtaining technology for intercepting
ballistic missiles, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is reportedly feeling growing pressure of ballistic
missiles from neighboring Syria and Iran.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Turkish military ties have been developing rapidly
since they signed a defense cooperation pact in early 1996, which
has provoked widespread criticism from the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
The pact allowed Israeli fighter pilots to fly training planes
in Turkish air space, as Israel agreed to help upgrade Turkey's
fighters.
</P>
<P>
During the annual defense meeting in March, the two sides
discussed ways of boosting military cooperation, including the
possibility of jointly manufacturing a main battle tank for Turkey
and Israeli sale of airborne early warning systems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
