<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Conduct Census in 2001 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria is to conduct a new
population census by the year 2001, the National Population
Commission said.
</P>
<P>
According to commission Chairman, Lt.-Col. Chris Igbokwe
Wednesday, the presidency has already agreed in principle to
lease money for necessary preparations for a successful census.
</P>
<P>
full preparations will begin after the forthcoming
international conference on the country's 1991 census figures,
which will be attended by demographers from all over the world,
he said.
</P>
<P>
noting that Nigeria might not afford a successful census
alone, the chairman called on international population agencies
for financial assistance, the Punch paper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
But he did not give the figure expected to be in need for the
planned census.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Population Fund has earlier pledged support
for the exercise, by training personnel and supplying equipment.
</P>
<P>
According to the 1991 census, Nigeria had a population of 88.5
million, the 10th largest in the world at that time. This
accounted for 19.2 percent of the total sub-Saharan population,
with a density of 95.8 persons per sq km.
</P>
<P>
The figures remained valid, the chairman said, adding that it
was not correct that some international agencies projected
Nigeria's population had risen to 120 million.
</P>
<P>
Going by the 1991 census figure, the current population should
be between 107 and 108 million in the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's population growth rate now is 2.83 percent annually,
according to him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
