<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Press Expands Coverage on Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese press has
significantly expanded its coverage of environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey conducted by a nongovernmental environmental
organization shows that China's 76 major newspapers carried an
average of some 300 reports on the environment during 1997, an
increase of 40 reports on 1996 and double the figure for 1995.
</P>
<P>
The reports covered wide-ranging areas from concerns over local
neighborhood pollution to broad ecological issues such as the
world's oceans, endangered species and the ozone layer.
</P>
<P>
Zang Yuxiang, deputy-director of the State Environmental
Protection Administration's Pollution Control Department, said
that press coverage has promoted China's environmental protection
drive and has led to solutions for a number of difficult problems,
including pollution along the Huaihe River.
</P>
<P>
Chinese citizens have also recognized the power of the press in
terms of environmental issues. "Reports on the environment have
been carried in newspapers and on radio and TV on almost a daily
basis in recent years," according to Beijing resident Zhao Gengyi.
</P>
<P>
China Central TV (CCTV) is currently televising a series of
programs on interrupted water flow in some sections of the Yellow
River. A number of Beijing newspapers dedicated extensive coverage
to the "dust storm" which blew through the capital last
week. Today's edition of Beijing Youth Daily front-paged three
environmental stories and four photos covering animal protection,
air and water pollution.
</P>
<P>
The press is also focusing on air quality, with numerous
related reports carried by both the regional and national
media. Twenty-four cities including Beijing, Shanghai and Nanjing,
announce weekly air quality reports via newspapers, radio and
television.
</P>
<P>
Many Shanghainese consider air quality as an important index
when choosing where to live, with the trend attracting increasing
attention from Beijing citizens.
</P>
<P>
The State Environmental Monitoring Center publishes weekly
reports on the air quality in 20-plus cities in a number of
national newspapers including the China Daily, Economic Daily and
Legal Daily. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 08:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Adopts New Law on Islamic Medical Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Iran's conservative-dominated
Majlis (parliament) has adopted a new law banning medical care
practitioners from servicing people of the other sex.
</P>
<P>
The Jomhuri Islami (Islamic Republic) newspaper reported on
Thursday that the law passed by the Majlis on Wednesday
stipulates that only men can provide medical services to men and
only women can treat other women.
</P>
<P>
This law is in accordance with strict Islamic regulations,
which forbid any physical contact between men and women who are
not related or married, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The law demands all private and public medical institutions,
including hospitals, clinics, laboratories, etc. to respect
Islamic regulations.
</P>
<P>
In any special case which needs medical personnel from other
sex, the law says, a third person from the same sex of the patient
or his or her relative should be present.
</P>
<P>
Any one violating the law will face severe punishments
including fine and closure of medical institution, the daily
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
