<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Water Resources To Enter International Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- China's water-resource sector has
great potential to grab a larger share of international markets.
</P>
<P>
China should make full use of its technological and equipment
superiority in the sector, said Zhu Dengquan, vice-minister of
Water Resources in an interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
So far, China has five units engaged in developing
international cooperation with overseas investors in
water-resource development. Twelve water-resource companies have
rights to manage import and export businesses by themselves.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, China had signed more than 500 cooperative
contracts with overseas partners in water-resource development
involving a combined contractual investment of 1.9 billion
U.S. dollars, according to a report provided by the International
Cooperation Department of the ministry.
</P>
<P>
And project contracts are in the majority, with contractual
funds reaching 1.6 billion U.S. dollars. The value of contract
labor for technical expertise in the water-resource sector was 110
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report shows that China owns world-level advanced
technologies for building dikes and dams. The technologies for
building small-size hydro-power stations and studying silt are
generally acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
During the Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000), China has
succeeded in developing more than 30 items of exported
technologies in the sector, of which several have entered
international markets.
</P>
<P>
China has exported more than 10 water-resource technologies
such as technologies for building small-size hydropower stations
and planting thorn bushes to 32 countries and regions, including
the United States, Japan, Brazil, Thailand and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
To date, China has also exported water-resource equipment such
as small-size hydraulic turbines and hydrologic forecast monitors
to 11 countries, involving a total of 29.7 million U.S. dollars in
contractual funds.
</P>
<P>
In addition, China has launched water-resource projects in
Southeast Asia, the Middle East, Africa and North America, valued
at 530 million U.S. dollars of contractual investment.
</P>
<P>
China began such overseas projects in the 1960s, Liu Zhiguang,
a high-ranking ministry official, said, adding that China has
established water-resource cooperative links with more than 60
countries and regions. It has also set up 26 water-resource
offices overseas.
</P>
<P>
However, he said China should make great strides in improving
international cooperation in water-resource development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
