<HEADLINE> US Expert's New Approach to Hyacinth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- A visiting U.S. Professor
suggested a new approach to deal with water hyacinth, the New
Vision reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Barry Costa-Pierce, a professor in California University and
fellow of the American Institute of Fishery Research, said his
conception is a "cage culture."
</P>
<P>
His conception accepted the weed as a blessing but not a curse
as others considered, Costa said.
</P>
<P>
"My vision is one of community development," he said, adding
that the weed can be developed into feed in an industrial scale.
</P>
<P>
But he did not elaborated.
</P>
<P>
The rampantly growing weed is imposing a serious environmental
problem to Uganda, Kenya and Tanzania as it suffocates water
organisms in Lake Victoria.
</P>
<P>
Most experts suggested to spray chemicals to eradicate the
weed.
</P>
<P>
But local environmentalists argued that the chemicals may
cause other environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
After all, the weed has little possibility of being completely
eradicated, the professor noted.
</P>
<P>
Costa had worked in Malawi and Indonesia before as an
aqua-cultural specialist.
</P>
<P>
The specialist will meet local experts in the National
Environment Management Authority and Makerere University, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
Costa also suggested Uganda should develop "cage culture"
industry in local waters to produce Nile Tilapia.
</P>
<P>
Nile Tilapia is one of the staple fishes in the country. But
it failed to find its way into the markets in Europe, the main
market for Ugandan fish products.
</P>
<P>
There is a very large market in the United States for Uganda's
Tilapia, Costa said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
