<HEADLINE> 1.3M Kenyan Children Denied Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Some 1.3 million eligible
children are out of school in Kenya due to poverty, inadequate
financial resources and other socio-economic problems, the Daily
Nation newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Education Minister Kalonzo Musyoka said in Durban,
South Africa Wednesday that the figure is likely to increase to
4.4 million by the turn of the century as the school dropout rate
continues to rise.
</P>
<P>
"In view of this, current government efforts are geared toward
enhancing access and equity at all levels," he said at a
week-long U.N.-sponsored caucus which brings together African
education ministers.
</P>
<P>
Musyoka said the focus was now on closing gender gaps in the
provision of education by initiating concrete intervention
measures to improve the enrolment of girls and sustain their
participation in the school system.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government had introduced bursaries and subsidies
to assist children from poor families especially girls, to get
access to education, he said.
</P>
<P>
Plans were underway to increase the number of women teachers,
particularly in science and technology, to popularize the
subjects among female learners, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed concern over the crises affecting higher
education in Africa, saying the institutions suffered low
financial support, lack of learning and teaching facilities and
high student enrolment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
