<HEADLINE> Infectious Disease Cases Rising in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Health has
reported a rise in the incidence of infectious diseases, saying
that hepatitis, tuberculosis, sexually transmitted diseases (STDs)
and AIDS are afflicting more Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Viruses infected about 192 of every 100,000 Chinese last year,
compared with 167 of every 100,000 people in 1996, the ministry
announced today in a statistical report.
</P>
<P>
The incidence of hepatitis, gonorrhea and measles rose over
1996 while that of dysentery and typhoid fever declined.
</P>
<P>
However, the mortality rate as a result of infectious diseases
was fairly low compared with non-infectious diseases such as
cancer and heart attacks, the report said. About 33 of every 10
million people died of infectious diseases last year.
</P>
<P>
"China has built a nationwide network which can effectively
monitor, report and control infectious diseases. A national
immunization project for children also helped control polio,
diphtheria, whooping cough and tetanus," the report said.
</P>
<P>
Health officials admit that some infectious diseases which had
been well-controlled in China are forming new epidemics such as
tuberculosis and STDs.
</P>
<P>
Acquired immune deficiency syndrome (AIDS) has been emerging as
a new public health problem in China as a result of drug abuse and
the STD epidemic.
</P>
<P>
The incidence of AIDS, which affected one of every 10 million
Chinese last year, was thought far less than a true number
"because lots of cases were hidden," according to some AIDS
experts.
</P>
<P>
These experts believe China has had at least 150,000 to 200,000
people infected by the AIDS virus, despite the 8,303 cases that
were reported by the Ministry of Health last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Rampant in Malawi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The AIDS pandemic has reached
"crisis proportions" in Malawi and half of skilled workers in the
country may die of the disease within the next decade.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail Thursday quoted a report on an AIDS
assessment study released last week in Malawi as saying that more
than 50 percent of skilled workers in Malawi may die of AIDS
within the next decade.
</P>
<P>
This has aroused fears in both official and public circles
that the country will lose much of its needed skilled personnel.
</P>
<P>
"For Malawians, the risk of HIV infection can be almost
entirely attributed to unprotected intercourse with an infected
partner," says the World Bank funded report.
</P>
<P>
However, the majority of sexually active Malawians -- the most
vulnerable group, scorn the use of condoms, says the report.
</P>
<P>
It added that base-line data about truck drivers indicate that
multiple partners are common and condom use is below 50 percent.
And the military is hesitant to monitor HIV prevalence for
security reasons, but in 1991, about 62 percent of blood donors
from the armed forces were HIV positive.
</P>
<P>
Random interviews conducted in the country's urban areas
indicate that many people in the sexually active group have a
negative attitude regarding condom use.
</P>
<P>
The report indicates that AIDS deaths will be the single
largest determinant of life expectancy in Malawi and that a
projected life expectancy of 57.4 years by 2010 is expected to
decrease by more than 13 years due to AIDS alone.
</P>
<P>
Other statistics indicate that the clinical burden of AIDS
will increase markedly and the epidemic may peak at about 70,000
cases per year during the middle of the next decade.
</P>
<P>
Further, states the assessment, current HIV/AIDS prevalence
levels cause grave concern for the future development of Malawi.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0211 </DOCNO>
