<HEADLINE> Hainan Province Reverses Economic Downward Trend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, April 23 (Xinhua) -- South China's Hainan Province, the
country's largest economic zone, has reversed a downward trend in
economic growth, according to acting governor Wang Xiaofeng.
</P>
<P>
The last five years marked the greatest fluctuation in the
economic growth of Hainan, which was part of Guangdong Province
before being turned into a province and special economic zone 10
years ago, Wang said today at a meeting of the provincial People's
Congress.
</P>
<P>
Boosted by a red-hot real estate market, Hainan reported
extraordinary economic growth between 1992 and 1994, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
However, Hainan's economic growth rate was lower than the
national average for the next three years as the central
authorities increased macro-economic control.
</P>
<P>
"Our economic growth rate was 4.8 percent in 1996 and 6.7
percent in 1997, and this indicates that our economy has bottomed
out and begun to pick up again," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that Hainan's industrial incremental
value rose from 2.04 billion yuan in 1992 to 5.13 billion yuan in
1997, up an average of 11.3 percent each year.
</P>
<P>
Hainan's gross domestic product is expected to grow an average
of more than 8 percent in the next five years, according to Wang.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that Hainan will continue to follow its industrial
revitalization plan and has set its industrial growth rate at 12
percent for the next five years. The rate is about 4-to-5 percent
higher than that for agriculture and the service industry.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the smooth accomplishment of its industrial goals,
Hainan will beef up its effort to develop industries such as
chemicals, building materials, foodstuffs, medicine, electronics,
machinery and information, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Hainan will also continue to follow a policy of opening-up,
with particular emphasis placed on expanding its commodity and
service trade, improving the investment environment, and building
several export-oriented industrial development zones, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
