<HEADLINE> Graft, High Rates in Kenya Worry British </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Minister of State for
Trade and Industry Barbara Roche said British business people
were concerned about corruption and high interest rate in Kenya's
money market.
</P>
<P>
Although British investors were keen to invest in Kenya, they
were also concerned about insecurity and the recession in the
economy, she said after meeting with Kenyan Minister for
Industrial Development Francis Masakhalia Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Britain's investment in Kenya fell to 23 million Pounds
between 1996-1997, from 50 million Pounds in 1989 and 1990.
</P>
<P>
Roche said Kenya has great potential especially in the area of
small scale enterprises, but the atmosphere at the moment was
unfriendly, local press reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the crime and high interest rates, investors were
also concerned about the tattered infrastructure in this east
African country, she noted.
</P>
<P>
British investors, Roche added, want all the problems that
could hamper the success of their businesses addressed as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
The British government was also interested in the
liberalization process being undertaken by the Kenyan government,
she said.
</P>
<P>
In reply, Masakhalia said the Kenyan government was committed
to revamping the economy and appealed to trading partners like
Britain for support.
</P>
<P>
Kenya and Britain enjoy cordial relationship but the trade
between them was still in favor of Britain, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Kenya imported goods worth 21 billion Shillings (210.4 million
Pounds) from Britain and exported goods worth 15 billion
Shillings (150.3 million Pounds) to the country last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
