<HEADLINE> Tianjin Reports Rise in First Quarter Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The foreign trade volume for the
major north China port city of Tianjin grew by 15.5 percent to
2.04 billion US dollars during the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
A breakdown of official statistics reveal that quarterly
exports grew by 10.6 percent to 1.24 billion US dollars, with
imports surging 24.2 percent to 800 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Foreign-funded enterprises reported exports totalling 850
million US dollars during the quarter, up 20 percent on the 1997
period.
</P>
<P>
Further analysis revealed that processing trade accounted for
800 million US dollars, or 70 percent, of the city's total exports
for the quarter. Exports of machinery and electric products alone
accounted for 40 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Figures show a considerable decline in Tianjin's exports to
Southeast Asia during the first quarter due to the ongoing
financial crisis in the region. However, exports to Europe and the
Americas soared more than 30 percent on the 1997 period. 
</P>
