<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Machinery, Electric Product Exports to Hit 67 Billion U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- China's exports of machinery and
electric products will hit 67 billion U.S. dollars this year,
up 10 percent over last year, according to industry officials.
</P>
<P>
Industry exports have maintained their momentum despite
pressures from the Southeast Asian financial crisis, according to
Tang Zhongwen, chairman of the China Chamber of Commerce for
Import and Export of Machinery and Electronics Products.
</P>
<P>
The industry's exports were valued at 8.75 billion U.S. dollars
from January to February, up 2.22 billion US dollars for a 33.2
percent increase over the same period last year. Statistics show
that the industry's export growth to the European Union (EU) was
65 percent; Latin America, 56 percent; and Africa, 48 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Asian financial crisis has had a negative impact on
exports, but the industry's sales to Southeast Asian countries
only accounts for 8 percent of China's total exports of machinery
and electric products. Industry growth to the EU and other areas
has offset the impact of the Asian financial crisis, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
However, industry exports still face a severe challenge from the
Republic of Korea (ROK) and other countries.
</P>
<P>
ROK increased its exports because of the devaluation of its
currency and support by the International Monetary Fund (IMF),
intensifying competition with China in the international market.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, ROK's import demand decreased sharply because of its
economic difficulties. Statistics show that China's exports of
machinery and electric products dropped 22.4 percent in the
January-February period.
</P>
<P>
To meet the industry's goal of a 10 percent increase this
year, the mix of exports will turn to technology-intensive
products with high added value from labor-intensive, primary
processing of products.
</P>
<P>
China also expects to develop existing markets, including the
EU, and plans to carry out a strategy of developing well-known and
quality products and further exploring markets in Africa and Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
The machinery and electric industry has led China in exports
for three consecutive years. Exports reached 59.32 billion
U.S. dollars last year, accounting for 32.5 percent of China's
total exports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
