<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Sets Allocation to Tackle Y2K Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysian government has
agreed to allocate 30 million ringgit (8.108 million U.S. dollars)
to deal with the millennium bug problem in the government sector
despite the economic downturn, Energy, Telecommunications and
Posts Minister Leo Moggie said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Several measures have been taken by the government to tackle
the Year 2000 (Y2K) problem, including the establishment of a
national Y2K hearing committee which consists of umbrella agencies
from both the public and private sectors, he said at the national
workshop on "Y2K Problem."
</P>
<P>
He said the committee would have its first meeting Friday at
his ministry to plan, coordinate and report back to the government
on the measures that have been taken by all sections.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile the Y2K website was also launched Thursday and would
be the convergent point for solution providers and their clients.
</P>
<P>
"A Y2K project team has been established to guide, facilitate
and monitor actions taken by the government sector and to maintain
the website," Moggie said, adding the project team, which would
also maintain a registry of Y2K-compliance companies, was expected
to start operation on May 1.
</P>
<P>
Moggie said that the government had also taken further
initiatives by adopting the "Shell Year 2000 Survival Action Guide
and IBM Adjustment 2000" as measures to help companies assess and
identify the extent of the problem which they could face through
the Y2K website.
</P>
<P>
He said the government is also focusing on creating awareness,
providing guidance and avenues for consultation on the millennium
bug problem and coordinating action plans which need to be taken
by private sector agencies.
</P>
<P>
The Y2K problem is expected to occur because programs and
electronic devices or computer chips, for example, use the digits
"00" to represent the year 2000, the same number that represents
the year 1900 in the two-digit system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Technique To Help Curb White Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- An assembly line to produce
biodegradeable food containers using corn as the raw material will
be built in northeast China's Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
Shenyang Luhuan Biodegrading Technique Development
Corp. announced its plans at the ongoing Agro Expo China '98 in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
According to the Shenyang firm, the containers degrade 60 days
after being discarded. They can also be used as fertilizer or as
fodder for cattle.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the new technique from Germany will play an
important role in curbing China's white pollution.
</P>
<P>
Food containers made of plastic foam, which take a long time to
disintegrate, are the main cause of white pollution.
</P>
<P>
China now produces more than six million tons of plastic
products and discards one million tons as waste every year. Only
300,000 tons were recycled.
</P>
<P>
Facing a serious pollution problem, China's large cities --
such as Dalian, Chongqing, Guangzhou and Hangzhou -- have
announced a ban on the use of plastic bags or plastic-foam food
containers.
</P>
<P>
China's experts and plastic producers have tried their best to
find a new and environmentally friendly replacement. In addition
to paper food containers, Shanghai is now producing food
containers with vegetable fiber such as rice straw, wheat straw
and sugar-cane residue.
</P>
<P>
China's markets need 10 billion food containers every year, and
the output of environmentally friendly ones is only 1.5 billion,
according to a survey by the previous Ministry of Light Industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
