<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0730 GMT, April 23 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States on Wednesday promised to try to
shield Montenegro from any further sanctions against Yugoslavia
for its defiance of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
"We will be sensitive to the needs of Montenegro," Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright told reporters before talks with Milo
Djukanovic, president of Montenegro. Montenegro now is republic of
Yugoslavia. Washington was already giving Montenegro aid worth 5.9
million U.S. dollars, said Albright, adding that expanded aid
programs would be included in talks with Djukanovic.
(US-Yugoslavia-Montenegro)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton has ordered a study
on storing vaccines, antidotes and antibiotics to deal with any
chemical and biological warfare against U.S. cities, Attorney
General Janet Reno said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Those medications would be strategically placed throughout the
country under a procedure that would maintain the shelf life of
stockpiles and would facilitate their prompt availability in the
event of a major chemical or biological incident," Reno told a
Senate hearing. The administration was considering launching a
research and development program with industry and academic
experts to deal with new, genetically altered pathogens, or
bio-engineered germs, she added. (U.S.-Biochemical Attack)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thailand, Cambodia and the U. N. High Commissioner
for Refugees (UNHCR) will discuss here on Monday the repatriation
of some 64,000 Cambodians in Thailand before Cambodia's July 26
elections, according to the Thai Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The meeting follows a call by the ASEAN troika, which includes
Indonesia, the Philippines and Thailand, on the Cambodian
government to "facilitate" the safe return of displaced
Cambodians, and on the UNHCR to provide assistance so that the
Cambodians are back in their homeland "in time to participate in
the election process."  
</P>
</TEXT>
