<HEADLINE> Xiamen Attracts More Taiwan Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Xiamen, a special economic zone in
east China's Fujian Province, approved 66 overseas-funded projects
between January-March this year, including 29 projects funded by
Taiwan investors.
</P>
<P>
The 29 Taiwan-funded projects involved total investments of
54.2 million US dollars. First quarter figures indicate that seven
Taiwan enterprises out of a total of 30 foreign investors
increased their investments during the period, with total
increased investments for the former hitting 10.36 million US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The first Taiwan-funded enterprise was established in the city
in 1984, with the city government having since approved 1,520
related ventures involving total investments of 3.43 billion US
dollars. Some 1,193 Taiwan-funded enterprises are currently in
operation.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan investments mainly focus on manufacturing projects, with
projects in the power generation, the chemical industry, food
processing and textile sectors accounting for 70.9 percent of the
total.
</P>
<P>
The number of high-tech projects has grown on an annual basis,
with investments shifting from industry and agriculture to
services. Over 90 percent of Taiwan-funded enterprises earn
profits.  
</P>
</TEXT>
