<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Large Painting by Fu Baoshi to Be Auctioned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- A large landscape painting by Fu
Baoshi (1904-1965), whose previous work garnered the highest bid
in history for a modern Chinese painting, will be auctioned in
Beijing in early May.
</P>
<P>
The painting, the largest work thus far offered in a Chinese
auction, measures 3.26 meters by 2.43 meters. The work depicts
Mount Zijin and Xuanwu Lake, the symbols of Nanjing which was the
seat of the central government under the Kuomintang.
</P>
<P>
The painting, entitled "The Tiger Girt with Dragon
Outshines Days Gone By", was named in honor of a line of
poetry Chairman Mao Zedong penned to mark his army's successful
1948 effort to take Nanjing.
</P>
<P>
Fu completed the work in 1960 as an expression of his idea of
"outshining days gone by", according to his son Fu Ershi.
</P>
<P>
Fu Baoshi perceived "outshining" as heavy smoke pouring
from chimneys, or the Chinese concept of modernization in the
1960s.
</P>
<P>
The chimneys outshine a distant backdrop of green mountain and
a lake surrounded by willows, according to local collectors.
</P>
<P>
The painting is expected to sell for between 4-5 million yuan,
a price much lower than the record lot entitled Ode of the
Beauties went for 10.78 million yuan. Last Autumn's auction was
handled by the China Guardian Auction Co. Limited.
</P>
<P>
The large painting is part of 2,800 piece lot valued at an
estimated 80 million yuan. Guardian will hold this year's Spring
Sale from May 5-11.
</P>
<P>
The six categories of lots will be: Chinese paintings, oil
paintings, sculptures, curios, jewellery, and stamps and coins.
</P>
<P>
Guardian was China's first auctioneer of art objects and will
celebrate its 5th anniversary on May 18. In the past five years,
it has held eight sales with over 10,000 pieces of art, with 450
million yuan in sales. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
