<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Vajpayee Government Faces Challenges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Since the swearing-in ceremony
here on March 19, two Union cabinet ministers of the Bharatiya
Janata Party (BJP)-led government have resigned or been sacked due
to corruption cases and more tainted ministers are expected to
follow suit.
</P>
<P>
Corruption cases and infighting among the BJP coalition
partners have become big hurdles and challenges for the fledgling
Vajpayee government to deal with.
</P>
<P>
A city court in Chennai, capital of Tamil Nadu in southern
India, framed charges against Union Surface Transport Minister R.
Muthiah and his whole family members on April 7 after finding
prima facie evidence against them in a case pertaining to
accumulation of disproportionate assets worth 4.57 million rupees
(0.119 million U.S. dollars). Muthiah resigned the following day.
</P>
<P>
Union Telecommunication Minister Buta Singh was sacked by Prime
Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee on April 20 due to his involvement
in bribery case of MPs in 1993 to save the minority Congress
government headed by P. V. Narasimha Rao as well as the pressure
from BJP's major ally All-India Anna Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam
(AIADMK).
</P>
<P>
In her letter to Vajpayee on April 18, AIADMK supremo
Jayalalitha asked the prime minister to drop tainted
Telecommunication Minister Buta Singh, Urban Development Minister
Ram Jethmalani and Commerce Minister Ramkrishna Hedge, who have
time and again criticized her during the infighting among the
BJP's coalition partners.
</P>
<P>
The resignation of Buta Singh has further sharpened the
differences and disputes among the partners. In his press
conference shortly after he was sacked from the cabinet on April
20, Buta Singh accused the prime minister of betraying him and
protecting other tainted persons. He said he decided to withdraw
his support to the BJP government and form a new party.
</P>
<P>
Ram Jethmalani has not made public his reply letter to the
prime minister for the comment on Jayalalitha's demand for his
resignation so far. Ramkrishna Hedge Wednesday said that he
favored the BJP-led government at the center seeking a fresh
mandate from the people instead of succumbing to the blackmail
tactics by the AIADMK.
</P>
<P>
On Jayalalitha's demand for his resignation, Hedge said, "The
charges have been repeated one million times. I have never been
asked to resign in my life. If necessary, I will resign myself."
</P>
<P>
In order to solve differences among BJP allies, some members
have proposed to set up a coordination committee holding regular
meetings to discuss various problems and disputed issues. The
AIADMK leader is opposed to setting up of such coordination
committee, which plans to hold its first meeting here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
According to the schedule announced by official sources, the
BJP-led government will table regular budget for 1998-99 and
several important bills to Parliament when it is convened in the
last week of May. The government is expected to face another acid
test during the forthcoming Parliament session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
