<HEADLINE> Economics, Coop Dominate Mkapa's Visit to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Economic progress, cooperation
and building a free and prosperous Africa are the dominant themes
being developed in the state visit of President Benjamin Mkapa of
Tanzania, ''the Herald'' daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The comments were made after Mkapa arrived in Harare Wednesday
on his four-day state visit to Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa and Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe and their
delegations spent most of the first day of the visit in
discussing matters of mutual concern, with economics at the
forefront, said the report.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to widen the scope of relations on the economic
front.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe told journalists that his talks with Mkapa also focused
on regional peace and stability and economic integration within
the Southern African Development Community (SADC).
</P>
<P>
''We also discussed the Great Lakes, and Comoros issue on how
to bring the two sides together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa made a special appeal for assistance as Tanzania faces
the loss of about a quarter of the harvest this year.
</P>
<P>
The El Nino phenomenon is wreaking havoc in Tanzania and the
country will have to rely on the goodwill of regional neighbors
and the international community at large to meet a food deficit.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa told Mugabe that his country was facing a crisis and
would be looking outside its borders for assistance to feed
thousands of people who were facing starvation.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said food aid to Tanzania would form part of a bulk
bilateral cooperation arrangement to be agreed by the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The themes of economic cooperation, and the building up of
Africa using this cooperation, dominated the addresses the two
presidents made Wednesday night at a state banquet hosted by
Mugabe for Mkapa.
</P>
<P>
They stressed as development challenges were faced, political
stability, national unity and concord, regional peace and
security had to be maintained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
