<HEADLINE> Dhaka Opens Special Courts to Recover Bad Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has opened two special
courts to revive its financial sector which has been seriously hit
by bank loan defaulters, English newspapers here reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Based in Dhaka and Chittagong respectively, the Bankruptcy
Court and Financial Court started functioning after a ceremony
held in Dhaka on Wednesday and attended by Bangladeshi Law
Minister Abdul Matin Khasru and Bangladesh Bank (central bank)
Governor Lutfar Rahman Sarkar.
</P>
<P>
The Bankruptcy Court is the first of its kind in the country.
</P>
<P>
Since 1991 nearly 64,000 cases have been filed with the
financial loan courts, of which 15,637 had been disposed of, the
central bank governor said at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that there are 48,363 cases still pending with the
financial loan courts while 1,000 new cases are being filed every
three months.
</P>
<P>
By December 1997, defaulted loans had amounted to 136.18
billion taka (about 2.96 billion U.S. dollars), accounting for 35
percent of the total loans of 402.63 billion taka (about 8.75
billion dollars), he stated.
</P>
<P>
It becomes impossible to recover the overdue loans due to the
loopholes in the law and lack of law enforcement, Sarkar added.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the two courts would be able to realize the
overdue loans through speedy trials.
</P>
<P>
"Stern action will be taken against the bank loan defaulters to
revive the banking sector," the law minister said, adding, "We
must be harsh against the willful defaulters as people of the
country are being deprived of proper banking services."
</P>
<P>
A number of bank and government officials were also involved in
the default culture, he said. "They should be singled out as the
nation wants to get rid of them."
</P>
<P>
Though the percentage of corrupt officials is "microscopic," it
is due to them that "the banking sector has been mismanaged," he
said. The nation's existence would be in "difficulty" "if the
situation continues to prevail," he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
