<HEADLINE> U.S. Seeks to Exempt Montenegro From Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Wednesday
promised to try to shield Montenegro from any further sanctions
against Yugoslavia for its defiance of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
"We will be sensitive to the needs of Montenegro," Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright told reporters before talks with Milo
Djukanovic, president of Montenegro which is part of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Albright praised Djukanovic for "an ability to see the
possibility for political dialogue and a different sense of
direction for the people" in the region.
</P>
<P>
Washington was already giving Montenegro aid worth 5.9
million U.S. dollars, said Albright, adding that expanded aid
programs would be included in talks with Djukanovic.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Djukanovic, who defeated a Milosevic protege,
Momir Bulatovic, in elections last October, told reporters he
neither wants independence for Kosovo, nor favors the status quo
in the province.
</P>
<P>
"A dialogue must start in Kosovo, and it is our opinion that
this dialogue must involve the presence of a third party," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Tensions escalated in February when conflict erupted between
Yugoslavian authorities and Kosovo's ethnic Albanians who wanted
independence from Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia stripped Kosovo of its autonomy 1990, angering
Albanians who make up 90 percent of the population in the
province, and strongly opposed any external meddling in the Kosovo
issue.
</P>
<P>
Major powers have already imposed some sanctions on Yugoslavia
due to its strong-arm approach to the ethnic Albanians, and have
given Belgrade until Saturday to start talks with the Albanians.
</P>
<P>
Next week, diplomats from the United States, Britain, France,
Germany, Russia and Italy are meeting in Rome to consider whether
to apply pressure on Belgrade on behalf of Kosovo's Albanians.
</P>
<P>
Djukanovic also ruled out the possibility that Montenegro seeks
independence from Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the citizens of Montenegro wish to live in a
federation with Serbia," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
