<HEADLINE> Former Greek President Karamanlis Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Former Greek President Constantine
Karamanlis died earlier Thursday of natural causes. He was 91.
</P>
<P>
Karamanlis, who was hospitalized with a lung infection on April
7, suffered a sudden relapse and died without recovering
consciousness at 1:40 A.M. local time, the semi-official Athens
News Agency (ANA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Karamanlis, who founded Greece's New Democracy Party (ND),
served as the country's prime minister four times and was twice
head of state.
</P>
<P>
He ordered a referendum in 1974 in which most people voted for
the abolition of the monarchy and the establishment of a
presidential republic in its stead.
</P>
<P>
Karamanlis, who was born in 1907 in Proti near Serres, northern
Greece, was elected to the Greek Parliament for the first time in
1935 as an MP for the Peoples Party from the Serres region.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released Thursday, Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis praised Karamanlis for the leading role he had played in
Greece's bloodless transition from dictatorship to democracy and
the tireless efforts he had made in guiding Greece to the European
Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
