<HEADLINE> U.S. Studies Measures to Defend Against Biochemical Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
has ordered a study on storing vaccines, antidotes and antibiotics
to deal with any chemical and biological warfare against U.S.
cities, Attorney General Janet Reno said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Those medications would be strategically placed throughout the
country under a procedure that would maintain the shelf life of
stockpiles and would facilitate their prompt availability in the
event of a major chemical or biological incident," Reno told a
Senate hearing.
</P>
<P>
She said the administration was considering launching a
research and development program with industry and academic
experts to deal with new, genetically altered pathogens, or
bio-engineered germs.
</P>
<P>
The administration was also considering relocating the nation's
laboratories in a strategic way so that they could quickly
identify any chemical or biological warfare agent, she said.
</P>
<P>
She noted that the potential consequences of chemical or
biological attacks could be "even more catastrophic" than the
terrorist attacks against the United States in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
She mentioned the bombings of New York's World Trade Center in
1993, Oklahoma City's federal building in 1995, and Saudi Arabia's
Khobar Towers in 1996.
</P>
<P>
She said the administration would work closely with the Energy
Department's national laboratories, academic experts and private
industry to address the threat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
