<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Needs Big Money for Health Care After Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's East Kalimantan needs
7.2 billion rupiah (about 930,000 U.S. dollars) to provide
medicines, infusions and radiological equipment to handle health
problems caused by forest fires in the province, a local official
said.
</P>
<P>
Data collected by provincial inventory teams showed that East
Kalimantan needs such a big amount to help people suffering from
respiratory problems, pneumonia, eye irritation and diarrhea, HA.
Waris Husien, an official of social affairs, said on Wednesday in
the provincial capital of Samarinda, according to reports reaching
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Forest fires have since January swept through about 400,000
hectares of area in East Kalimantan, causing a financial loss of
about 7.5 trillion rupiah (938 million dollars) and health
problems to the people there.
</P>
<P>
At least 4,000 people in the province are now suffering from
respiratory problems, 3,000 from diarrhea, 10 of whom already died
-- and thousands of others from pneumonia and eye irritation.
</P>
<P>
East Kalimantan is predicted to experience the worst
forest/land fires in 15 years. In 1982/83 the province was
estimated to suffer the biggest damage in the world from
forest/land fires by losing 3.6 million hectares, official sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Fires still break out in some parts of the province, especially
around the Bukit Soeharto conservation area and Kutai National
Park. About 538 hot spots have been spread out in Samarinda,
Balikpapan and Kutai. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
