<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Revises Amounts for Legal Determinations of Larceny </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- China recently increased the
amount required for a legal determination of larceny from at least
300 yuan (27 U.S. dollars) to 500 yuan (about 60 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In a document issued jointly by the Supreme People's Court, the
Supreme People's Procuratorate and the Ministry of Public
Security, this readjustment was explained as fitting the change in
China's economic and social conditions.
</P>
<P>
According to this document, the starting point qualifying "a
relatively large amount of stealing" is 500-to-2,000 yuan (60 to
250 U.S. dollars); for "a huge amount of stealing," it is
5,000-to-20,000 yuan (600 to 2,500 U.S. dollars); for "an
extremely large amount of stealing," it is 30,000 to 100,000 yuan
(3,750 to 12,500 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The document states that -- within the listed ranges of
starting points -- each province, autonomous region and
municipality can set its own detailed standard for larceny.
</P>
<P>
According to Chinese law, the amount stolen is an important
factor for establishing the penalty.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme People's Procuratorate recently issued a notice
asking procuratorates at all levels to make a serious
self-examination to avoid abuses of power and to execute the law
more strictly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
