<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Says Asian Financial Crisis Affecting World Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Asian economies will experience
further slowdowns in growth rates in 1998 due to the financial
turmoil, while the outlook for the global economy this year will
depend on a satisfactory response to the crisis, the Asian
Development Bank said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In its "Asian Development Outlook--1998" released here, the
Manila-based bank said the Asian financial crisis would cause a
slowdown in world growth by about one percentage point in 1998,
and in trade by about half a percentage point.
</P>
<P>
In Asia last year, the report said, the crisis contributed to a
further slowdown in the growth rate to 6.1 percent, and the rate
is projected to be about 4 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"The strength of the People's Republic of China and its
currency will become the anchor for regional economic stability in
1998," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that despite the Asian financial crisis that
began in last July, the growth of the world economy was strong at
3.2 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
This was not only a higher rate than in 1996, but also exceeded
the average for the preceding five years by 0.9 percentage point,
it said.
</P>
<P>
"Continued solid growth in the United Kingdom and the United
States underpinned this favorable economic performance, which was
aided by a strong recovery in Canada and a gradual revival of
economic activity in continental Europe," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The world trade grew exceptionally rapidly in 1994 and 1995,
slowed down in 1996, but rebounded in 1997 to 9 percent because of
a recovery in trade among the countries of the Organization for
Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD).
</P>
<P>
While the industrial economies experienced uninterrupted growth
with modest inflation, the bank said, several Southeast Asian
economies went through an unprecedented, cataclysmic financial
crisis last year.
</P>
<P>
"Unless these countries manage to resolve the crisis, its
adverse effects will spill over not only to other Asian economies,
but also to other regions, undermining the industrial economies'
current robust performance," it warned.
</P>
<P>
However, the bank said, dealing with such crisis successfully
is beyond the capacity of any individual country, and requires a
coordinated effort that involves the major industrial economies
and the international financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
The bank said the Asian financial crisis is already affecting
private debt repayments to the industrial economies, as Asian
companies and plant projects canceled or postponed a number of
payments due in early 1998.
</P>
<P>
Export growth in industrial countries will fall in 1998, partly
because of the collapse of purchasing power in the Southeast Asian
economies, and partly because of increased competitiveness from
Asian exports, especially from South Korea, as a result of the
large currency depreciations in the region, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The ADB said that a substantial redirection of trade flows is
likely to occur in 1998, and thus the trade deficit with Asia is
expected to narrow from about 42 billion U.S. dollars in 1997 to
less than 10 billion dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
On the impact of the crisis on the growth rate of industrial
countries, the bank said the output of the 29 OECD economies grew
by 3 percent last year, the highest rate since 1989, but the Asian
crisis will cause a fall of 0.6 percentage points in output and
0.5 percent in export growth in the OECD countries.
</P>
<P>
According to the bank, the Asian crisis will also affect
economic growth in Africa and Latin America this year.
</P>
<P>
"The recent financial crisis in Asia will have repercussions
for Africa's growth in 1998, especially as those Asian countries
have become some of Africa's fastest growing trading partners," it
said.
</P>
<P>
The bank said East and Southeast Asian currency depreciations
are projected to have an impact on the Latin American region,
which is likely to lose export competitiveness.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
