<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Warns of Risks, Uncertainties for World Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
warned Thursday that failure to address the Asian financial crisis
will not only exacerbate Southeast Asia and South Korea's economic
problems, but will also further undermine the growth momentum in
the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
In a report, "Asian Development Outlook--1998," which was
released here, the ADB said the on-going financial crisis in
Southeast Asia and South Korea has left these economies in
disarray and "the most important policy challenge for the world
economic community is to devise a satisfactory response.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the bank said, the crisis is already projected to slow
the growth of the United States, the European Union and the OECD
(Organization of Economic Cooperation and Development) countries
by 1 percentage point and of Japan by 1.5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
A full commitment to economic and policy reform is a
prerequisite for early recovery and sustained future growth of the
afflicted Asian economies, it said.
</P>
<P>
"The measures these governments, particularly those of
Indonesia and (South) Korea, take in 1998 to deal with the private
sector's maturing large external debt will inevitably determine
these economies performance," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
It said risks exist not only with respect to the East and
Southeast Asian economies, but also with respect to other Asian
countries that are not directly affected by the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
These economies, such as those in South Asia and the Central
Asian republics, are at various stages of economic reform process,
the bank said.
</P>
<P>
"Uncertainties remain about the level of commitment and
implementation and about the speed with which these economies will
respond to the reform program," it said.
</P>
<P>
The bank said the stability of the Chinese renminbi and the
Hong Kong dollar will remain "an important factor in the region's
economic stability."
</P>
<P>
Uncertainties also exist with respect to further liberalization
of the world trading environment, which is an important
determinant of the dynamics of the global economy, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of difficulties facing Asian currency and financial
markets, the bank said, the World Trade Organization agenda to
liberalize trade in financial services will pose a challenge in
1998 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
"Globalization is a double-edged sword. It has brought with it
many economic benefits in the form of increased competition and
more efficient allocation of resources," it said.
</P>
<P>
"At the same time, however, the resulting high mobility of
short-term capital can quickly cause major financial problems for
any country that international markets perceive as having major
policy shortcomings," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The ADB also said that an important "exogenous" source of
uncertainty is climatic, as this year's economic performance of
Southeast Asian countries will amply testify.
</P>
<P>
Although structural changes of the past three decades have
reduced the importance of agriculture as a source of income, it
continues to be an important determinant of growth in many Asian
developing economies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
