<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Assesses Economic Impact of Asian Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
said Thursday that a modest economic recovery in Southeast Asia
from the current financial crisis is expected in 1999, but
recovery to pre-crisis economic growth rates and per capita income
levels will take a number of years.
</P>
<P>
The situation could deteriorate further if the current currency
and stock market crisis widens, or spills over into a full-fledged
banking crisis with a run on banks, the bank said in its "Asian
Development Outlook-1998" which was released here.
</P>
<P>
The "most discernible impact" of the financial crisis has been
a sharp decline in private capital inflows to Southeast Asian
countries, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
As investors' confidence was shattered by the crisis which
began last July, Southeast Asian countries suffered net private
capital outflows of 12 billion U.S. dollars in 1997, compared to
net inflows of 93 billion dollars in 1996, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1997, maturing short-term debts in several
Southeast Asian economies were not rolled over, it said.
</P>
<P>
"This resulted in an estimated outflow through commercial banks
of 21 billion dollars, as compared with inflows of about 56
billion dollars in 1996," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The ADB said the affected countries' reserves fell sharply
despite official assistance and a narrowing of their combined
current account deficit.
</P>
<P>
The impact of the crisis on the financial sectors of Southeast
Asian countries has been also enormous, according to the bank.
</P>
<P>
Although data on financial distress are still very tentative,
the bank said, they indicate serious problems with respect to
non-performing loans and capital adequacy of financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of non-performing loans to total loans varies among
the affected countries, ranging from 10 percent in the Philippines
to 35 percent in Indonesia, it said.
</P>
<P>
The Manila-based bank said the financial crisis has also posed
a serious liquidity problem for enterprises in the affected
countries, constraining the ability of enterprises to take full
advantage of the depreciation in the currency values.
</P>
<P>
"Without a major improvement in the credit situation,
enterprises will not be able to fill export orders, and the
possibility of an export boom leading these countries out of the
crisis will be remote," it said.
</P>
<P>
Given that the Asian crisis was not an outcome of
macro-economic imbalances, but was caused principally by
structural weaknesses in the financial and corporate sectors,
problems will take time to redress, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, it said, if the governments concerned implement
the appropriate policies and reform institutions, the impact of
the economic crisis is likely to be "moderate, and at worst,
medium rather than long term.
</P>
<P>
Despite the crisis, the bank said, the longer term outlook for
the region is far from bleak.
</P>
<P>
The capacity for resource mobilization, the reasonable good
infrastructure, the favorable demographics, the open trading
system and the general commitment to macro-economic prudence
should stimulate economic growth, which should resume once
appropriate adjustment policies are implemented and take effect,
it said.
</P>
<P>
Assessing the impact of the crisis on the world economy, the
bank said the crisis will reduce real gross domestic product in
OECD (Organization of Economic Cooperation and Development)
countries by around 0.6 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
For the world as a whole, the reduction in GDP will be around
1.1 percent, the bank said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia to See Further Economic Slowdown in 1998: ADB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The growth rate of the Asian
developing economies slowed down further to 6.1 percent in 1997
from 7.5 percent in 1996 because of a financial crisis, and the
rate is projected to be about 4 percent in 1998, with some
recovery in 1999, the Asian Development Bank (ADB) said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In its "Asian Development Outlook--1998" released here, the
bank said that except for the Central Asian republics, gross
domestic product (GDP) in all sub-regions of Asia declined last
year, including the Pacific islands which experienced negative
growth.
</P>
<P>
"However, the most conspicuous slowdown was in Southeast Asia,
where the growth remained positive but declined to almost half of
the level achieved in 1996," it said.
</P>
<P>
As the financial crisis that is affecting Southeast Asia
dominated the last half of 1997, the growth rate of the sub-region
fell from 7.1 percent in 1996 to less than 4 percent in 1997, the
lowest figure in two decades, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
It said the economic outlook for the sub-region in 1998 is
"extremely uncertain" and will depend largely on the extent to
which governments can implement the various rescue packages of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
"Projections indicate that Southeast Asia (except Singapore,
which is divided into the category of the newly industrialized
economies) can expect negative growth of 0.4 percent in 1998," the
bank said.
</P>
<P>
"The huge private sector debt burden in Indonesia and Thailand
in particular will have a major impact on the economic performance
of Southeast Asia in 1998 and 1999," it said.
</P>
<P>
The Manila-based bank predicted a negative 3 percent GDP growth
rate both for Thailand and Indonesia in 1998, and a 1 percent
growth rate for them in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The bank also estimated that the Philippines' GDP will grow by
2.4 percent in 1998 and 4 percent in 1999, Malaysia by 3.5 percent
in 1998 and 4.5 percent in 1999, and Singapore by 3 percent in
1998 and 4.5 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
As a result of depreciation and the rapid increase in import
prices, inflation in Southeast Asia is expected to rise from 5.6
percent in 1997 to 12.9 percent in 1998, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
"Indonesia is projected to be particularly hard hit, with an
inflation rate of about 20 percent," it said.
</P>
<P>
But, it said, current account imbalances in Southeast Asia are
likely to improve in 1998, partly because of the slower growth,
and partly because of the improved competitiveness of exports due
to currency devaluations.
</P>
<P>
The sub-region's deficits are projected to improve to 6.1
billion dollars in 1998 and 900 million dollars in 1999, the bank
said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the economic performance in other sub-regions, the
bank said China as well as the newly industrialized economies
(NIES) -- Hongkong, China; South Korea; Singapore; Taipei, China
-- also experienced some slowdown in growth in 1997 but still
remained high at 6 percent and above.
</P>
<P>
The outlook for the NIES in 1998 will be influenced by the
Asian crisis and GDP is forecast to grow by only 2.2 percent, it
said.
</P>
<P>
Although the Asian crisis has not affected the Chinese economy
severely to date, the bank said, it is projected to undermine
economic performance slightly in 1998 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
"Growth in each of these years is projected to be about 7
percent. This will be partly the result of a weakening in demand
from those Asian developing countries that currently account for
about one third of the People's Republic of China's total
exports," it said.
</P>
<P>
The bank also said the growth rate for South Asian economies in
1997 declined to less than 5 percent from 6.8 percent per year
between 1994 and 1996, but will grow at an average rate of 6.4
percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan is expected to grow at 5.1 percent, two percentage
points faster than in 1997, and Sri Lanka by 5.6 percent, as
opposed to 6.3 percent in 1997, it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
