<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Defends IMF Programs for Crisis-Affected Economies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Key element required for rapid
recovery of Southeast Asian countries and South Korea is not the
traditional austerity measures, but structural reforms, the Asian
Development Bank (ADB) said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In an economic outlook released here, the bank defended the
reform programs led by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) in
these countries, saying that they are "much more broadly based
than traditional austerity programs to ensure macro-economic
balances."
</P>
<P>
Since the Asian financial crisis began last July, South Korea,
Thailand and Indonesia have sought IMF bailout, and started the
implementation of IMF reform programs.
</P>
<P>
"They (IMF programs) are designed to bring about structural
reforms that will strengthen financial systems, increase
transparency in both the public and private sectors, and open
markets, thereby restoring investors' confidence," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
To this end, the bank said, non-viable financial institutions,
including banks, are being closed down, while other weak, but
viable, institutions are required to produce restructuring plans.
</P>
<P>
Other proposed structural changes include strengthening
financial sector regulations and supervision, it added.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that to reverse the sharp slide in currency
values, the IMF programs also suggest steep increases in interest
rates and tight monetary policies to stem the outflow of capital.
</P>
<P>
On the social cost of the IMF programs, the bank said: "No
doubt, the impact of these reforms will be painful."
</P>
<P>
"However, the economic slowdown would have been much more
dramatic and the costs to the general population would have been
much more higher without the IMF-led assistance packages," it
said.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that managing a recovery is just as difficult and
demanding as managing a crisis.
</P>
<P>
Successful implementation of any policy reform or structural
adjustment depends on government commitment, political support and
institutional capability, it said.
</P>
<P>
The bank called on governments to be "single-minded" about
reform programs and about implementing them.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Sums up Lessons From Asian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
said Thursday that responsible fiscal management, prudent monetary
policy and greater exchange rate flexibility are important
elements that could help prevent a financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The recent experience of Southeast and East Asia indicate that
private capital flows can be an important source of development
finance, but if this flow is poorly managed, it can be extremely
destabilizing, the bank said in its "Asian Development
Outlook--1998" which was released here.
</P>
<P>
"Thus, the important lesson that emerges is that responsible
fiscal management, prudent monetary policy, and greater exchange
rate flexibility are important elements of a strategy to redress
these adverse effects of surges in private capital flow," the bank
said.
</P>
<P>
However, it said, before opening up the capital account,
institutional reforms are needed to improve the soundness of
economies' financial sectors to ensure that capital flows are well
managed.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the critical role of the banking system in allocating
capital, the bank said the health of the system largely determines
whether a country will be able to exploit the benefits of
financial integration and avoid its pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
"While many Asian developing economies have partially
liberalized and deregulated their financial sectors since the
early 1990s, their banking sectors are still weak and fragile," it
said.
</P>
<P>
To address the issue of the poor health of their banking
sectors, the bank called on these countries to reform
institutional structures, improve such areas as regulation,
supervision, and accounting, and upgrade the overall governance of
the sector to avoid the various financial sector frailties that
can lead to a financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The bank said the countries which have not been affected by the
crisis should also take measures to develop well-functioning
capital markets to reduce the risks of potential instability in an
integrated world.
</P>
<P>
According to the bank, actions are required in three major
areas:
</P>
<P>
-- Market infrastructure, which comprises the systems and
institutions required for trade and custody of security;
</P>
<P>
-- Corporate governance, including protection of property
rights, especially those of minority shareholders;
</P>
<P>
-- Disclosure of market and company information and control of
abusive market practices.
</P>
<P>
Reforms of business laws, such as bankruptcy procedures, are
also required, the bank added.
</P>
<P>
Referring to globalization, the bank said the financial crisis
has generated skepticism in many quarters about the benefits of
globalization, especially of financial integration with the global
economy.
</P>
<P>
As with trade in goods and services, capital flows between
countries generally benefit both sending and receiving countries,
it said.
</P>
<P>
However, it said, to benefit from globalization, the countries
need to prepare themselves for it, so that they can avoid its
adverse effects, including the volatility it may sometimes
generate.
</P>
<P>
"Globalization is a double-edged sword. It rewards good
policies and punishes bad ones," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
It said the difficulties the affected economies have
experienced are not grounds for inaction or for adopting measures
that will retard the liberalization process, it said.
</P>
<P>
"The benefits of globalization are too large to ignore," the
bank said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mountain City Seeking Approval for Rare Plant Reserve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOUu, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The mayor of Fu'an, a mountain city
in east China's Fujian Province, has finished preparing a
report as part of an application to set up a rare-plant
reserve.
</P>
<P>
"The report was prepared several months ago," said Lan Ruchun,
Fu'an's mayor. "We hope this will help to protect the alosphia
spinulosa, a rare plant under top state protection found in
mountains within our administrative border."
</P>
<P>
An official with the Fujian Provincial Forestry Department said
he was "very excited that a country-level city like Fu'an can take
such an initiative to protect nature even before its economic
take-off."
</P>
<P>
If the forestry department approves Fu'an's application, it will
then go to the provincial government, which has the final say in
the approval process.
</P>
<P>
According to Chen Dingyuan, a senior engineer with the local
forestry department, alosphia spinulosa is an endangered species
which once co-existed with the now-extinct dinosaur. Now it is
one of the eight types of plants under top state protection.
</P>
<P>
More than 3,000 alosphia spinulosa were recently discovered in
two mountain valleys near Guaxi Village, Xitan Township of Fu'an.
The tallest one is about 7 meters high, exceeding the record 6
meters indicated by the China Red Paper Book for Endangered Plants.
</P>
<P>
An expert from Fujian Normal University said that, based on
current materials, the distribution area of alosphia spinulosa in
Fu'an may be the world's largest and the best in higher latitudes.
</P>
<P>
"We first planned to construct a hydro-power station in the
area, but when the alosphia spinulosa was discovered we
immediately decided to stop plans for building the hydropower
station and set up a reserve there instead," said Xu Guichun,
secretary of the Fu'an City Committee of the Chinese Communist
Party.
</P>
<P>
He said that measures have been taken to protect alosphia
spinulosa and their environment as well as to raise the
conservation awareness of local villagers even before the
provincial reserve is approved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Human Resources Development Crucial for Future Growth: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The effective utilization of human
resources will play a crucial role in Asia's fast economic growth
in the next century, the Asian Development Bank (ADB) said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In its "Asian Development Outlook-1998" which was released
here, the bank addressed the important issue of the role of human
resources in Asia's future development.
</P>
<P>
"Developing Asia enters the new millennium with the potential
advantage conferred by a rapidly growing population and labor
forces." it said.
</P>
<P>
"However, this growth is by itself is not enough. To take full
advantage of the opportunities requires a major investment in
human resources and technological capability," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
Given the wide disparities in the levels of economic
development in developing Asia, the bank said, no single strategy
is applicable across the region.
</P>
<P>
But with the rapid pace of globalization and increasing
international competition, all the Asian developing economies will
need to face their specific problems of human resource development
sooner rather than later, it said.
</P>
<P>
"While the challenges are pressing, the rewards are high," the
bank said.
</P>
<P>
It said that an increase in the labor force is not by itself a
prerequisite for economic growth as it could merely result in
higher unemployment and greater poverty.
</P>
<P>
What is crucial is how this resources is enhanced, the bank
said.
</P>
<P>
"One of the key elements behind the (Asian) economic miracle,
and one that the relatively less developed Asian countries ignore
at their peril, has been the effective use and development of that
most fundamental of all resources, the people," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, the bank said, governments have a crucial role to
play in this area.
</P>
<P>
In many countries governments directly fund a large proportion
of spending on health and education, but despite the importance of
such expenditure, it is still often inadequate, it said.
</P>
<P>
"This is partly because the benefits from increased expenditure
on health, education, and training, although crucial for sustained
economic development, take a long time to materialize," the bank
said.
</P>
<P>
"Furthermore, they are not as immediately discernible as
expenditures on more tangible investments, such as building a new
factory or dam or improving infrastructure," it said.
</P>
<P>
The bank said governments in lowest income Asian countries
should allocate more public resources to primary and lower
secondary education.
</P>
<P>
This would enhance internal efficiency, as the social returns
to primary and lower secondary education tend to be much higher
than those to higher education in these economies, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The bank said the rapid growth rates some Southeast Asian
economies achieved in the past were no doubt partly influenced by
demographic factors and by an outward-oriented policy environment.
</P>
<P>
By using abundant cheap labor, these economies were able to
specialize in exports of labor-intensive products, it said.
</P>
<P>
"However, the era of rapid growth through the pursuit of
traditional, labor-intensive, low value-added production and
exports may be over, because of the adoption by other Asian
development economies," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The bank said the lessons from the current economic crisis are
not limited to the need for prudential regulations to govern
private financial institutions and for more general reforms of the
financial sector.
</P>
<P>
All the Asian developing economies can learn important human
resources lessons from the current crisis, including those
economies that are not facing the full brunt of the crisis, it
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
