<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chuan, Mahathir Supports Local Currency Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai
and his Malaysian counterpart, Mahathir Mohamad, have voiced their
support for efforts to facilitate trade by using local currencies
among members of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
Chuan and Mahathir met Wednesday night in Songkhla, southern
Thailand, and agreed that their finance ministers should carry out
the task, said Malaysian Foreign Minister Abdullah Badawi, who
accompanied Mahathir on his one-day visit to Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Both Thailand and Malaysia are seeking to push the proposal to
conduct trade in local currencies instead of the U.S. dollar,
Badawi was quoted as saying by major Thai newspapers Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir proposed last year that ASEAN countries conduct trade
in their respective currencies to reduce dependence on the U.S.
dollar.
</P>
<P>
"In order to implement that, there must be some mechanism to
settle this," Badawi said.
</P>
<P>
Chuan and Mahathir discussed a wide range of issues after
witnessing the signing of agreements for jointly exploiting gas
reserves in a joint development area lying in once-disputed
waters.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also agreed to promote border trade between the
two countries, according to Thailand's Foreign Minister Surin
Pitsuwan.
</P>
<P>
He said Mahathir agreed in principle to lift the ceiling on the
transit of perishable goods from Thailand to Singapore. Under a
1978 accord, Malaysia set a ceiling of 30,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
In return, Chuan agreed in principle to allow the transit of
Malaysian goods destined for Indochina, Surin said, adding that
both decisions would have to be formalized by memoranda of
understanding.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers also agreed on the demarcation of a
disputed border area at Pedang Besar. Chuan proposed the extension
of opening hours for the Betong-Perak, Golok-Kelantan and
Sadao-Perak border points, according to the reports. It is unknown
whether Mahathir accepted the proposal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
