<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Review: Robust Domestic Demand Crucial for China's Economic Growth Target (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- China has witnessed a slowdown in
economic growth over the past three months and has reached a
crossroads which will either be characterized by a
rebounding GDP, or by the further stagnation of robust
demand for both investments and consumption, according to Beijing
economists,
</P>
<P>
Estimates place the year-on-year GDP growth for the first
quarter of this year at 7.2 percent, some 0.8 percent lower than
the central government's target for the year. The robust economy
China has enjoyed for the past eight-odd years now faces the
threat of stagnation in the absence of efforts to stimulate demand
for investments and consumption.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Hanya, deputy director of Investment Research Institute
under the State Development Planning Commission, said the
financial crisis sweeping most Asian nations will most likely
result in zero increase, or even a small drop in China's exports
for the year. Increase in investments and consumption will be the
only two contributors to the targeted eight percent growth in GDP.
</P>
<P>
The slow increment in income levels over the past year will
most likely limit consumption increases to about three percentage
points of GDP growth, with the remainder supported by an expanded
investment scale, according to Zhang.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the growth rate in consumption will fluctuate
between 10-12 percent during 1998. Ensuring an increase in GDP
will require inputs in fixed assets to reach 16-18 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, veteran economists insist that the investment target
can be attained as long as the central government readjusts
financial policies and macro-control measures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> (Economic Review) Robust Domestic Demand Crucial for China's Economic Growth Target (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Liu Rongchang, a research fellow at the Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences, said that instead of loosening its control over
credits the central government should resort to such financial
inducements as subsidies, stocks and guarantees to attract money
from people of all walks of life into infrastructure, high-tech
and real estate projects.
</P>
<P>
The government should offer more preferential policies to
encourage the country's enterprises to carry out structural
reform, technical upgrades and the launch of new products as well
as stimulating exports, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
Qiu Xiaohua, senior economist for the State Statistical Bureau,
said that an abundant money supply will also be an important
guarantee for GDP growth. China plans to increase the broad money
supply by 16-to-18 percent this year. If that comes true, the
country should be on a smooth path to a GDP growth of 8 percent or
more.
</P>
<P>
In response to the idea of Qiu and other economists, Dai
Xianglong, governor of the People's Bank of China, told the World
Economic Forum this week that the central bank will "moderately
increase the money supply" to ensure an 8 percent growth in GDP
this year.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the government at all levels should raise more
capital by accelerating reforms in housing and water prices while
seeking more channels to get money by cooperating with state banks
and foreign firms, said Zou Shaoyan, vice governor of Sichuan
Province.
</P>
<P>
He added that both the central and local governments should
attach more importance to the profitability of their investment
projects to speed up capital circulation.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan Province plans to invest 118-to-120 billion yuan in
fixed assets this year, up 13.7 percent over the same period in
1997.
</P>
<P>
A zero increase is expected in Guangdong Province's investment
schedule, the investment plans by other provinces
register big increases over the previous year. Regional
economic powers such as Shandong and Jiangsu even outline an
increase of 15 percent in investment in fixed assets.
</P>
<P>
Economists noted that these investment schedules by local
governments lay a sound basis for increases in funding for the
whole country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
