<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Press Issues Code of Conduct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Press Council of Thailand
(PCT), formed last year as a self-governing body of the Thai
press, has unveiled the country's first Code of Conduct for
newspapers in a bid to create "a clean press."
</P>
<P>
The code, a copy of which was received here Thursday, comprises
30 articles setting strict rules for newspapers and reporters.
</P>
<P>
For example, Article 17 states that newspapers "must not
publish pictures which are obscene or horrifying" while Article 15
demands respect for human dignity by everyone involved in the news
and protection of human rights, especially when children, women
and the socially underprivileged are concerned.
</P>
<P>
A PCT official explained that this means that from now on,
publishing nude photos or scary pictures of accident or murder
victims is prohibited, no suspect shall be branded as a
"cold-blooded murderer" or "rapist" and people's personal lives
can no longer be exposed unless the disclosure serves public
interests.
</P>
<P>
According to the code, complaints against newspapers or
particular reporters or writers can be initiated by the affected
party, public representatives such as non-governmental
organizations, or consumer organizations. A subcommittee will be
set up to investigate complaints. Newspapers found to have
violated the code will be told to publish the PCT ruling and an
apology.
</P>
<P>
In the case of a ruling against an individual reporter, his or
her organization will be told to consider a punishment and inform
the PCT as soon as possible of any action taken. In case the PCT
rulings are not obeyed, council members may be asked to publish
the rulings in their respective newspapers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
