<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment Encouraged in Water-Resource Development (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The report said that China's need for water provides another
bright opportunity for overseas investors, particularly in the
cities.
</P>
<P>
The ministry plans to increase its water-supply capacity from
rivers and reservoirs by 10 billion cubic meters a year to prevent
overuse of underground water leading to subsidence.
</P>
<P>
The report said that many hydro-power and water conservation
projects built in the 1950s and 1960s are aging and need technical
improvements, which create other investment opportunities for
overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
"Local water-resource bureaus plan to generate funds to
renovate these old projects through joint investment, cooperation
or selling off part of the property rights," the report stated.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Tanlin, a leading official of the Foreign Investment
Office, suggests overseas investors consider buying shares of the
"China Middle and Small Hydro-Power Generation Fund," which is
being established by the Bank of China. MWR proposes the
hydro-power projects to receive investment.
</P>
<P>
He said that the fund has aroused the interest of many
financial institutions and companies abroad.
</P>
<P>
Yuan said that MWR is also engaged with the Canadian government
in a feasibility study for some investment projects in the Aojiang
River in east China's Fujian Province.  
