<HEADLINE> Europe Understands Africa Better Than US: Kenyan FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Foreign Minister Bonaya
Godana said here Wednesday that European countries seem to have a
better understanding of African countries than the United States
in providing aid for the continent.
</P>
<P>
Godana made the remark upon his arrival in Helsinki for an
unofficial visit designed to forge closer bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
U.S. president Bill Clinton expressed in his African trip last
month that the U.S. is seeking to a transition from providing
development aid to supporting bilateral trade in developing
U.S.-African relations.
</P>
<P>
Such a change of policy on the part of the U.S. government
contains the risk that the U.S. might boost its right to have a
say in the internal affairs of African countries, the foreign
minister said. He did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
As all economic blocs are operating across the world on an
increasingly frequent basis, all countries, including those in
Africa, should make a special effort to enhance relationships with
each other through international cooperation, Godana said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Organization of African Unity (OAU) has played an
important role in promoting economic development in African
countries.
</P>
<P>
Finland is one stop of the Kenyan Foreign Minister's northern
European trip which aims to strengthen relations between Kenya and
those countries.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Finland, Bonaya held talks with Finish
Development and Cooperation Minister Pekka Haavisto and Foreign
Trade Minister Ole Norrback. They exchanged views on bilateral
relations and development aid and other issues of common interest.
</P>
<P>
Kenya has been the traditional recipient of Finnish bilateral
aid. In 1996, Finland provided 15 million Finish Marks (3 million
U.S. dollars) to Kenya for joint projects of forest preservation
and water resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
