<HEADLINE> China Develops Yellow River Hydropower Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, April 23 (Xinhua) -- China is currently trying to
develop hydropower resources on the upper reaches of the Yellow
River in order alleviate power shortages in northwest China.
</P>
<P>
Ding Zhongzhi, director of the Northwest Power Administration,
noted that seven hydropower stations on the upper reaches of the
river, the second longest in the country, have a total generating
capacity of 5.62 million kilowatts.
</P>
<P>
Operational plans for three large hydropower stations on the
river's section flowing through Qinghai Province have been
completed, and two thirds of total available water resources on
the upper reaches of the Yellow River are prime for development.
</P>
<P>
Ding noted that power shortages not only limit local economic
development, and also reveal the vast potential for related
development.
</P>
<P>
Experts have paid special attention to abundant water resources
on the upper reaches of the Yellow River. Plans for the 918-km
section between Longyangxia and Qingtongxia call for the
construction of 25 medium- to large-sized hydropower stations with
a total generating capacity of 15.88 million kilowatts.
</P>
<P>
Research carried out in Qinghai and Gansu provinces, and the
Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region provides ample proof that the
development of hydropower stations on the upper reaches of the
Yellow River will involve minimal relocation efforts and
investments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
