<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment Encouraged In Water-Resource Development (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China is also preparing to raise water prices to reduce wastes
and increase profitability in water-supply projects, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
"Out of concern for the farmers, who consume 80 percent of the
country's water, prices will be raised in a range of 1-to-1.5
cents per cubic meter of water, with different prices charged to
different social and economic sectors," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have always stressed that water-resource development is a
social undertaking, and now we treat it as an industrial sector."
</P>
<P>
The 59-year-old official said that China hopes to have its
current water law revised this year, with more efficient clauses
arranged for foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
"China's water law was promulgated in the planned-economy era,"
he said, "but some clauses no longer suit conditions and need
revision because China has made deep inroads in building a
socialist market economy in the past 10 years."
</P>
<P>
The Ninth National People's Congress, the legislature, has
shown a positive attitude toward a thorough review of the water
law, he said.
</P>
<P>
With administrative, price and legal progresses, the minister
is confident of a boost in foreign investment in water-resource
construction.
</P>
<P>
A report from the Foreign Investment Office of the ministry
said that 90 percent of hydro-power potential in China is
untapped, which leaves a wide arena for overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
The ministry provides electricity through hydro-power
generation to more than 800 counties, which are located mainly in
China's central and western parts.
</P>
<P>
The report noted, "but these counties' racing economic
development cries out for more electricity."
</P>
</TEXT>
