<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Use Radar to Control Air Traffic in Guangzhou, Shenzhen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 23 (Xinhua) -- China will convert to radar air
traffic control at airports in Guangzhou and Shenzhen on July 1 to
increase the number of flights.
</P>
<P>
At present the Beijing area is the only one using radar for air
traffic control.
</P>
<P>
An official with the air traffic control bureau of the Civil
Aviation Administration of China (CAAC) said that, with the
operation of Hong Kong's new airport, the flight volume is
expected to increase in Guangzhou and Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
The official said the only way to increase flights is to use
radar control. In most of China's airports, controllers have to
calculate aircraft location based on its take-off time and air
speed.
</P>
<P>
To guarantee safety, the official said, flights have to
maintain a 150-kilometer separation to allow for errors in
calculation. After installing radar, however, the spacing between
flights can be reduced to 20 kilometers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
