<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Spreads Fast in Mexico's Rural Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The number of acquired
immuno-deficiency syndrome (AIDS) patients has increased 277
percent in the rural areas of Mexico over the past seven years,
the Ministry of Health said.
</P>
<P>
In a press release on Wednesday, the ministry said a total of
150,000 persons have been infected by the human immuno-deficiency
virus (HIV) in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Mexico now ranks as third on the American continent with
the highest number of AIDS patients, just slightly behind the
United States and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said the spread and growth of AIDS is caused by
the country's geographic, economic and social conditions.
</P>
<P>
Mexico shares a long common border in the north with the United
States. This zone registers the largest amount of AIDS infections.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the southern border also represents a high risk area
for the transmission of the deadly virus. It is believed that 93
percent of the prostitutes working in the zones with the greatest
number of infections are illegal immigrants from neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
Xochitl Castaneda, an analyst for the Investigation Center of
Population Health of the National Institute of Public Health,
admitted that messages and strategies to promote "safe sex" have
failed to bring the desired results.
</P>
<P>
She added that one of the most important challenges in
implementing prevention strategies is how to change the behavior
of individuals for personal and public well-being. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nordic States to Set Up Joint Peacekeeping Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Four Scandinavian countries are
to set up a joint peacekeeping force subject to the United Nations
and the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
The decision to set up the Nordic Coordinated Arrangement for
Military Peace Support was made by defense ministers from Sweden,
Finland, Denmark and Norway at a meeting in Kiruna, northern
Sweden, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
An army brigade of 3,000 to 4,000 servicemen and armored
vehicles is expected to be trained and equipped in the next few
years.
</P>
<P>
Swedish Defense Minister Bjoern von Sydow said that both the
U.N. and NATO wanted Nordic countries to share greater
responsibilities in maintaining peace and stability in Europe.
</P>
<P>
He said that Scandinavian states would strengthen their
cooperation in mobilizing an efficient force within a reasonable
time to assist the international community.
</P>
<P>
The Nordic countries now provide peacekeeping forces at the
company or battalion level of no more than 800 servicemen, mostly
on peacekeeping missions in Bosnia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
