<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exit Polls Banned in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Commission on Elections has
announced that no exit polls will be allowed during the May 11
elections in order to prevent any "unreasonable" confusion that
may arise, a leading Philippine newspaper said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Commissioner Manolo Gorospe said Wednesday that the poll body
will not accredit any application for the conduct of exit polls on
May 11 in order to "prevent confusion among voters" on who is
winning or losing.
</P>
<P>
He said the commission might issue a resolution banning the
conduct of exit polls to discourage further petitions for
accreditation, according to the Philippine Star.
</P>
<P>
In an exit poll, voters emerging from the polling place are
asked at random whom they voted for. Results of such polls are
usually announced immediately. They are popular in the United
States and are usually considered highly reliable.
</P>
<P>
But Gorospe said the Philippine political culture is not ready
for exit polls.
</P>
<P>
"We have this culture that nobody loses and everybody is a
winner. If we conduct an exit poll and the result is released even
before the counting is finished, we could have a chaotic
situation," Gorospe said.
</P>
<P>
The commission is not expected to come out with the results of
the presidential polls in less than a week, as it took the poll
body three weeks in the 1992 elections to complete its counting.
</P>
<P>
Gorospe revealed that already, a local media outfit has sought
accreditation for an exit poll. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
