<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Noted Economists on East Asian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- One lesson China can draw from
the East Asian financial crisis is that extensive economic growth
will not last, pointed out noted Chinese economists.
</P>
<P>
Wu Jinglian and Wei Jianing, both noted economists, wrote in an
article carried by the bimonthly magazine Reform that high speed
economic growth for almost 20 years before the financial crisis
misled leaders in many East Asian countries. But risks were
inherent in the increasingly investment-based economic growth.
</P>
<P>
According to them, extensive growth has also been a problem
accompanying China's economic development. Although the government
has tried to promote the transformation of the pattern of growth
by reforming the economic system since the early 1980s, the
transformation has so far made little progress.
</P>
<P>
Over-heated investment in a few industries and duplicate
construction will make enterprises vulnerable to market
competition, they added.
</P>
<P>
The financial crisis also told China that the bubble economy is
dangerous, they observed.
</P>
<P>
Over-heated stock markets and property markets could be found
in those Asian countries which were to suffer from the financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
In China, the stock market was once filled with the bubble
element. Although inflation is under control now, financial
speculation is still going on. Therefore, China should always be
on the alert against economic bubbles, they said.
</P>
<P>
The economists suggested that China guard against the financial
risks now.
</P>
<P>
During the rapid economic growth in recent years, enterprises
in East Asian countries borrowed loans from inefficient
investment, which contributed greatly to the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
In China, the low efficiency of State-owned enterprises forced
the government to support them with extensive funding from State
banks, resulting from non-performing loans. It is high time to
deal with these financial risks, they noted.
</P>
<P>
Other lessons that China can learn from the crisis include that
enterprises must be separated from the government, the government
should interfere less in economic activities; and that the quality
of the government's policy-making system is crucial to sound
economic development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980423.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
