<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rican Banana Exports Fall Due to "El Nino" Phenomenon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rica's banana exports fell
5 percent in 1997 from the previous year mainly as a result of "El
Nino" weather phenomenon, Jorge Sauma, General Manager of the
National Banana Corporation (Corban), said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica exported 101 million boxes of bananas, each weighing
18.4 kilograms, in 1997 against 106.5 million boxes in the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
"El Nino" phenomenon has caused the weather to change abruptly
along the coastline of the Latin-American Pacific Ocean, leading
to reductions in the banana output.
</P>
<P>
Sauma pointed out that exports have also been affected by some
restrictions in the banana trade. "Companies started to demand
increasing quality, this reduced the exports," he stated.
</P>
<P>
However, the manager of Corbana added that a recovery in banana
exports in the last six months of the year is expected. In 1998,
banana exports could range between 105 and 107 million boxes and
that an increase in productivity was also foreseen.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica is the second largest exporter of bananas only after
Ecuador, but holds the largest productivity in the world.
</P>
<P>
The country's banana exports are bounded mainly to the North
American market, which consumes 52 percent of the total. The
European Union purchases almost the resting 48 percent, while a
small portion is exported to Asia, mainly to China and Japan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
