<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Small Loan Program Introduced To Help Poor Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Gongshan County is a remote,
poor area in southwest China's Yunnan Province, with local
farmers having little knowledge of the outside world.
</P>
<P>
In recent months, they have been talking about Bangladesh which
is only several hundred km away from the county but used to be
felt by the villagers as far as a country on the other side of the
globe.
</P>
<P>
What has made Bangladesh known to Gongshan farmers is the Small
Credits Scheme, which was created by the Agameen Bank of
Bangladesh and has succeeded in helping millions of poor rural
families eliminate poverty in its birthplace, as well as in dozens
of other developing nations.
</P>
<P>
China's Foreign Ministry has tried hard to spread the
Bangladeshi successful poverty-elimination practice in the
country, since the Chinese Embassy in Dhaka made detailed reports
on the scheme in the mid-90s.
</P>
<P>
For the past few years, the small loan program has been carried
out on a small scale on a trial basis in Yunnan, central China's
Henan Province, and the Tibet Autonomous Regions.
</P>
<P>
The successful results of these experiments have enabled the
central government to adopt the scheme in all poor areas in the
country, including the whole of Yunnan.
</P>
<P>
Four of Gongshan's five townships have provided four million
yuan from the central exchequer to implement the program, with
the exception of Dulongjiang Township that cannot try out the
program because of harsh national conditions.
</P>
<P>
The motto of the Bangladeshi program is "providing the loans
only to poor families and wives". In China, some revisions have
to be made to suit local conditions.
</P>
<P>
"We mainly target families that are poor but ambitious," says
Yang Ruxiao, head of the Small Credits Scheme Work Station, a
Chinese version of the Agameen Bank, in Puladi Township,
Gongshan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
