<HEADLINE> Belgium, Romania Drawn in World Cup Warm-Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Two similar goals scored in each
half of a Belgium-Romania World Cup warm-up game tied the two
teams at one all on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The visitors proved their worthiness as World Cup group G seed
by opening the scoring first at half time though they had been
pressed hard during the entire game.
</P>
<P>
Gheorghe Hagi, Romania's 1994 World Cup hero, set up the score
by chipping to the left an accurate pass which striker Viorel
Moldovan drove to the far bottom corner for the lead.
</P>
<P>
Romania had called up a record of 16 foreign-based players for
its 20-man team for Wednesday's game, including Hagi and Gabi
Popescu.
</P>
<P>
Belgium also recalled its foreign-based stars including regular
goalkeeper Filip de Wilde, Marc Wilmots, Luc Nilis and Michael
Goossens.
</P>
<P>
It was Nilis, who plays for the Dutch club of PSV Eindhoven,
found the ball at the left of the penal area and chipped it past
Romania's goalkeeper Bogdan Stelea to the far bottom corner for
the equalizer at the 77th minute.
</P>
<P>
The game developed into a rather physical one during which the
referee had to fish out the yellow cards more than a dozen times
to caution players from both sides to calm down and restrain from
high kicking and foul tackling.
</P>
<P>
It was the second drawn game on home turf during Belgium's
run-up toward this summer's World Cup finale in France. The
Belgians, best known as the Red Demons, first beat the United
States 2-0 before being pindowned by Norway to a 2-2 tie. 
</P>
</TEXT>
