<HEADLINE> Boeing Posts Profit in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Boeing showed a profit of 50
million U.S. dollars in the first quarter, a profit substantially
below the year earlier quarter of 540 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The cost of grappling with production problems was blamed for
the cuts of the first-quarter earnings. The company lost money
with the third and fourth quarters of 1997 and for the year.
</P>
<P>
Boeing had disclosed earlier this month that continuing
bottlenecks in the assembly of its new 737 models would cost the
company 350 million dollars before taxes in the first quarter this
year.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the production snags have cost Boeing about 3 billion
dollars before taxes and put heavy pressure on management to get
production back on track and restore the company's financial
health.
</P>
<P>
Boeing's sales climbed 24 percent in the first quarter to 12.9
billion dollars, on the strength of increased deliveries of
commercial jets. It delivered 108 planes in the first quarter
compared with 77 a year ago.
</P>
<P>
A statement of the company quoted its chairman Phil Condit as
saying that Boeing still expects to deliver 550 commercial jets
this year, including 225 of the newer 737s that have been delayed.
Increased production rates for the 757, 777 and 747 are on
schedule.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Seattle manufacturer is monitoring the Asian
financial situation, which has the potential to hurt future
commercial jet deliveries, especially of big models such as the
777 and 747. So far no cancellations have been announced, but the
company has said as many as 60 deliveries could be affected in the
next two years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
