<HEADLINE> Canada Takes New Steps to Assist Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government announced
some new initiatives to assist in the Middle East peace process
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The new initiatives include a contribution of 4 million dollars
(2.8 million U.S. dollars) for reconstruction efforts in
Palestinian communities, and 2.5 million dollars (1.75 U.S.
dollars) for improving municipal services in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
Canada will also set up a Canadian Representative Office in the
West Bank/Gaza, and take new efforts to accelerate the relocation
of Canada Camp residents with their community in Gaza, according
to a government news release.
</P>
<P>
These initiatives flow from recommendations made by a recent
Canadian task force to the region, which examined Canada's
involvement in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the initiatives, Canadian Foreign Affairs Minister
Lloyd Axworthy said Canada's approach is to "identify practical
and constructive steps" that show the pursuit of peace is in the
interest of all the people in the region.
</P>
<P>
"By working to improve the living conditions of Palestinians,
Canada is helping to build an environment where all people in the
region can enjoy the fruits of peace," added Diane Marleau,
minister for international cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
