<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK PM Blair Defends Decision to Accept Nuclear Waste </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
Wednesday defended his decision to give green-light to accepting
nuclear material due to be reprocessed in a nuclear plant in
Scotland from Georgia.
</P>
<P>
The Labor government's decision to accept these dangerous
materials has triggered widespread outcries in Britain, with
environmentalists describing the decision as "ill-conceived and
dangerous".
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the House of Commons, Blair insisted that
reprocessing some five kilograms of nuclear materials at a remote
Scottish plant would add only marginally to the stockpile of
nuclear waste there.
</P>
<P>
Blair noted that the United States had already taken some 600
kg of unused highly enriched uranium from Kazakhstan while Russia
had taken 137 kg from Iraq since the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
"Other European countries are making other contributions. That
is the reason why we thought it important to do what we did,"
Blair added.
</P>
<P>
On why the government failed to announce the plan beforehand,
Blair explained that the operation had been kept secret because
there were fears that the laboratory in Georgia could be taken
over by Chechen rebels opposed to the Georgian government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
