<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Urges Malaysian-Backed Firm to Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government
has affirmed its commitment to all legally binding agreements
with a Malaysian-backed power company but maintained that it will
not agree on the extraordinarily high power tariffs.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the State House Wednesday said the
implementation of the International Power Tanzania Limited (IPTL)
project will make Tanzania increase the tariffs by nearly 50
percent at the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The country already has the highest costs of electricity in
the east Africa region.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, IPTL, a private Malaysia-Tanzania joint venture, won
a contract to build a 100 megawatt thermal power plant station
worth 150 million U.S. Dollars in the northern outskirts of Dar
es Salaam. The construction of power station, lasting 12 months,
is expected to end by August.
</P>
<P>
But the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World Bank
(WB) later said the project will be an unacceptable burden on
Tanzania's fragile economy because of the proposed wholesale
tariff of 21 cents per kilowatt hour is too high.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the prices of electricity are likely to be
even higher in 1999 and in the subsequent years.
</P>
<P>
It further said that the government therefore called on IPTL
to meet the obligations in negotiating for power tariffs on good
faith to ensure that they are based on "actual, reasonable and
affordable rates."
</P>
<P>
The statement said this could be achieved by working out the
capital and operational costs of IPTL, and give fair return to
the investors, and at the same time leave tariff affordable by
the state power company TANESCO, the national economy and the
people.
</P>
<P>
Last week, after three days of fruitless talks between IPTL,
the Energy Ministry and TANESCO, the government angrily ordered a
seven-member Malaysian delegation representing IPTL to leave the
country immediately.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources explained the reason for the dispute was
that TANESCO had defaulted to buy electricity from IPTL.
</P>
<P>
Denying it was a deportation, the statement said, "The
government and TANESCO assert their rights under the agreements
they signed while leaving the door open to resolve all disputes
with IPTL through reasoned negotiations."
</P>
<P>
It stressed that when embarking on the negotiations, IPTL
should recognize that the government represents a sovereign
state, free to select internal and external experts, advisors and
partners in order to promote and protect the country's interests,
and is accountable to its citizens.  
</P>
</TEXT>
